turing nor FDI have always been accompanied with economic growth. Latin America is a case in point. Akyuz (2004) discusses the limits to focusing on export-led industrialization extensively, and points to the rising ratio of manufactured exports to GDP in developing countries without a significant upward trend in the ratio of manufacturing value-added to GDP. As put by Akyuz: In major exporters of manufactures in the South, export values have constantly exceeded manufacturing value-added during the past two decades, and the gap has increased further as exports have grown faster. Thus, the increase in the share of developing countries in world manufacturing exports has not been accompanied by a concomitant increase in their shares in world manufacturing value added. These comparisons relate to value-added generated in developed and developing countries, rather than incomes earned from manufacturing activi- ties. The value-added left in developing countries is smaller and the income earned by industrial countries is larger if account is taken of profits earned by [transnational corporations] on their investment in developing countries (pp. 9-10). Overdependence on foreign resources from exports implicitly requires the assumption that external demand will always exist. Foreign resources for domestic capital accumulation may not always be available when the receiving country needs the investment in particular sectors of industry. This is a very bold assump- tion given that globalization has been integrating many outsiders into the system rather quickly.24 Debates on this issue go back to Nurkse\u2019s theoretical discussion on development from the 1950s.25 Based on the pos- sibility that foreign resources might be insufficient, Nurkse\u2019s theory points out the significance of industrializa- tion depending on domestic market expansion as a better strategy. Domestic demand is certainly a crucial factor, but how to turn an export-driven growth into growth that depends on domestic demand becomes very important at this point. Moreover, there would not be any motivation to invest if there is no demand in an economy. Thus, demand-centered policies are also important. The significance of domestic demand with respect to domestic investment in capital accumulation is critical for a FG pattern of development. This is also mentioned in Akamatsu\u2019s original contribution. Growth in domestic demand proves to be a strong policy for rising employment as well. For instance, estimates show that Chinese export growth over the period 1997-2002 contributed to 2.5 million jobs per year (Feenstra and 23 Backward linkages refer to the purchases of primary supplies (for example, raw materials), secondary supplies (for example, semi-finished products), and tertiary supplies (for example, services such as packaging). Forward linkages imply the marketing and distribution of goods and services in the local economy (UNCTAD 2001). 24 See Blecker and Razmi (2007) for a detailed discussion of a fallacy of composition outcome of the export-led industrialization when all developing countries are specialized in manufactured exports. Price competition led by the growth of output in developing countries has significant effects on the short-run growth of output in developing countries that are specialized in manufactured exports. The study pres- ents estimations showing that depreciation relative to competing developing country exporters increases the home country\u2019s growth rate at the expense of its competitors\u2019 growth. The authors suggest that real depreciations might be contractionary for some major manufacturing exporters.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3fd920c6-96bf-4c53-89d2-abeb62a90e0e": {"__data__": {"id_": "3fd920c6-96bf-4c53-89d2-abeb62a90e0e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "042b949499e7181cf09404d7f02c204d4b76b7157ef584394febec4f224c5c5d"}, "2": {"node_id": "adf34d9f-6394-44f8-b72e-c1513b21ed4a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bb397e4ea3d33ef4f33af72db7a3484b67232ecd2a03a67221eac284bb018c64"}}, "hash": "977ce71938cb2a7a2d2cb90ed8dbb19e1b7b485b8ec7487dd2f93c2192624589", "text": "The authors suggest that real depreciations might be contractionary for some major manufacturing exporters. 25 See Kregel (2007) on Nurkse and the role of finance in development. 34 Hong 2007). Even though exports have become increasingly important in stimulating employment in China, it is argued that the same gains could be obtained from growth in domestic demand given the stagnant nature of exports prior to 2002. Second,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7423edda-144b-46bc-8747-ea95630d36c4": {"__data__": {"id_": "7423edda-144b-46bc-8747-ea95630d36c4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9c34a2252b50df27e5827550c8741c926121a0c202637b7b96d2010ddd71a96c"}}, "hash": "9c34a2252b50df27e5827550c8741c926121a0c202637b7b96d2010ddd71a96c", "text": "besides the size of FDI inflows, the quality of FDI is also crucial for the needs of the receiving economy. As Lall (2000) puts it: It is important for countries to secure not just more, but also higher quality FDI. This means attracting more advanced [multinational corporation] activities, oriented to international mar- kets, providing advanced technology, using and creating sophisticated skills, and taking the host economy into a dynamic system of international production (p. 338). Selective targeting policy, which has been emphasized repeatedly in development, has raised attention to this new conceptualization of FDI inflows from a qualitative approach. Criteria such as knowledge intensity and provisioning of resources for innovation have formed new policy measures for FDI. As expected, high quality FDI has stronger backward and forward linkages leading to faster economic growth. In implementa- tion of these policy measures RTAs and BTAs might again play a significant role. As pointed out by Shrank (2003), regional development needs the integrated efforts of both sides of an investment. Third, the breakdown of FDI inflows by different sectors is another key issue. For instance, the composi- tion of China\u2019s FDI outflows have been similar to those of the Republic of Korea during the period 1988-2002, and to Japan\u2019s outflows during the period 1968-1982, targeting resource-rich regions/countries in Latin America and Africa (see Tables 2.6 and B.3). Hong and Sun (2004) suggest that existing FDI patterns in the region provide supporting evidence for a FG pattern. However, such FDI outflows are conditioned on being resource-rich, and this develops a challenge for non\u2013resource rich neighboring economies. It is important to note that investment decisions are made by firms; similarly, external trade is pursued by exporting/importing firms, not by the governments. We do observe shifts in the composition of FDI outflows from China towards the services sector similar to what has been happening elsewhere over the last decade. Furthermore, spatial dualities, particularly in the Chinese economic structure, cannot be ignored. An implicit assumption behind FG-consistent FDI flows is the immobility of labour among different countries; thus, a country moves its labour intensive industries to another country. In China, despite some recent developments in labour regulations, the mobility of labourers is still limited. Accordingly, the gap in production costs due to the immobility of labour among different re- gions of the country partly explains the changing direction of capital flows from coastal areas to the inner land areas. Zhang (2007) shows evidence for a declining trend in the inner-coastal differences in capital formation since 2000. On the other hand, this might turn out to be a challenge for the close-by neighbors with respect to FDI potential. In general, we do see a FG pattern of development in FDI together with emerging China and India; however, one should consider that distance does matter greatly. The theory of economic geography presents some possibilities for neighboring countries located close by. Given the long distances between the coastal and inner regions of China, cheaper transportation costs make it plausible to see a change in the direction of FDI outflow towards these nearby neighbors rather than to the inner regions. With the rise of China and India, there are other benefits to exploit besides trade-related gains. How- ever, their rise also creates challenges, especially for relatively slow growing developing nations in the region. Nevertheless, research on regional integration processes in Asia indicates a wide range of opportunities for all as long as the momentum of economic integration is strong and political will is there. A full and robust integration clearly requires conscientious efforts from all related parties. 35 The general objective of this study is to explore whether there exists a potential for a FG pattern of develop- ment in the Asia-Pacific region within a regional integration process. More specific objectives include providing a framework to carry out the analysis and to pursue empirical assessments of the recent patterns of growth, trade, and investment flows, with a particular emphasis on emerging China and India. The fact that China and India have joined the successor geese family raises the question of whether other neighboring nations should worry about this development. In this respect, we seek to learn what are the possible opportunities and challenges for the countries in the region. In this study we propose a dynamic tool to examine the country sophistication level of exports. We look at whether there exist FG-consistent shifts in the countries\u2019 trade structure over time, and we explore the dynamic shifts in the division of labour among the nations in the region based on an empirical analysis of the sophistication indices of exported goods.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "08785db8-7876-4819-b14d-baa701417fb6": {"__data__": {"id_": "08785db8-7876-4819-b14d-baa701417fb6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "110f71c86b677147bea19c96f0c29c374c1c28b207aff293569f5c005047f50c"}, "3": {"node_id": "4bbea878-05a6-401c-a148-dd99478e3abd", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "11e84be0ed8e8b758e9160cc8c6e37c16853e8a519c4d3f57832e2245b97bf78"}}, "hash": "fe8fb5529c046f619d0e24cb66b9bd18d3700fc888ca4b3caf90dd19d733476b", "text": "Recasting the FG framework through sophistication curves, we have found that the evolution of the trade structure in the region over the last decade is consistent with a FG pattern of development. We assert that opportunities are available for other developing nations to benefit from increasing trade and investment potential that accompany the growing absorption capacities of emerging China and India. Nevertheless, these opportunities come with challenges, particularly for the slower-growing economies. These developing economies should pay attention to the following points: \uf06c The evolution of a FG pattern needs a holistic approach to regional integration through policies directed at trade, industrialization, and, hence, development. \uf06c The regional integration process should not only consider changes in trade policies, but the process needs to be evaluated using both quantitative and qualitative measures. \uf06c FG-consistent development includes an external trade policy, which is supported by a robust public policy along with an industrial policy. This has important implications for a human development-oriented approach to trade. \uf06c Domestic demand plays an important role in a FG pattern of development. Strong domestic demand establishes the required motivation for domestic investment and attracts FDI. \uf06c Latecomers following China and India should pay more attention to developing domestic demand, given that the transfer of labour-intensive jump-start industries from China and India, with their huge labour reserves, might take quite a long time. 5. Conclusion 36 \uf06c The criteria for receiving high-quality FDI inflows should include qualitative measures along with exist- ing quantitative measures. High-quality FDI is necessary for a country ultimately to join the process of an FDI-led FG pattern of development. The framework we propose here provides an initial step and a methodology for evaluating trade out- comes from an industrial development perspective. A more detailed analysis is required to explore the human development impacts of the regional shifts discussed here. In line with Akamatsu\u2019s argument for an extensive exploration of the process of industrial development, one needs to investigate the historical, political, and institutional structure of an economy in a regional development context. Further research could also focus on forming multi-dimensional sophistication indices to get a better picture of export dynamics. Analysis at more disaggregated levels of industries for an individual country could provide additional insights. These would require a more focused research, which would include the specifics of the changing social, political, institutional, and economic conditions of the individual countries of concern. 37 References Ahearne, A.G., Fernald, J.G., Loungani, P., and J. W. Schindler (2006), \u201cFlying Geese or Sitting Ducks: China\u2019s Im- pact on the Trading Fortunes of other Asian Economies,\u201d Board of Governors of the [US] Federal Reserve System International Finance, Discussion Papers, No. 887. Ahearne, A.G., J. G. Fernald, Loungani, P., and J. W. Schindler (2003), \u201cChina and Emerging Asia: Comrades or Competitors?,\u201d Board of Governors of the [US] Federal Reserve System International Finance, Discussion Papers, No. 789. Akamatsu, K. (1962), \u201cA Historical Pattern of Economic Growth in Developing Countries,\u201d The Developing Econo- mies, 1 (1): 3\u201325. Amsden, A.H. (1991), \u201cDiffusion of Development: The Late Industrialising Model and Greater East Asia,\u201d Ameri- can Economic Review, 81(2) (May). Batra, A. (2006), \u201cAsian Economic Integration ASEAN+3+1 or ASEAN+1s?,\u201d Working Paper No. 186, Indian Coun- cil for Research on International Economic Relations. Bernard, M. and J. Ravenhill (1995), \u201cBeyond Product Cycles and Flying Geese: Regionalization, Hierarchy, and the Industrialization of East Asia,\u201d World Politics, 47 (2) (Jan.): 171-209. Chen, Y. and E.K.Y. Chen (2006), \u201cGeoeconomic Implications of China\u2019s Emergence for East Asia,\u201d Paper pre- sented at the AT10 Research Conference in Tokyo, 3-4 Feb. 2004. Cheng, L.K.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4bbea878-05a6-401c-a148-dd99478e3abd": {"__data__": {"id_": "4bbea878-05a6-401c-a148-dd99478e3abd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "110f71c86b677147bea19c96f0c29c374c1c28b207aff293569f5c005047f50c"}, "2": {"node_id": "08785db8-7876-4819-b14d-baa701417fb6", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fe8fb5529c046f619d0e24cb66b9bd18d3700fc888ca4b3caf90dd19d733476b"}}, "hash": "11e84be0ed8e8b758e9160c