3bec1aa7d403c0114892dccaea670b08e1a"}, "3": {"node_id": "44131ea1-8a12-4086-aaf6-85d0b5535f2f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2fe2702ec2c737e4f56e71c1ef28450c7ef80356b36861467df69900cd20eedb"}}, "hash": "3f327751cc3a63178a915f177fd376a3b16b920ff0468afa5d13650f24117551", "text": "World Investment Report. Geneva: UNCTAD. UNCTAD (2007), World Investment Report. Geneva: UNCTAD. 40 UNCTAD (1996), Trade and Development Report. Geneva: UNCTAD. Voon, J.P. (1998), \u201cExport Competitiveness of China and ASEAN in the U.S. Market,\u201d ASEAN Economic Bulletin, 14 (3): 273-291. Wagle, S. (2007), \u201cProduct Fragmentation and Trade Integration in Asia,\u201d Unpublished Draft - UNDP Regional Centre for Asia Pacific, Colombo Office. World Bank (1993), The East Asian Miracle: Economic Growth and Public Policy. New York: Oxford University Press. Xing, L. (2007), \u201cEast Asian Regional Integration: From Japan-led \u2018Flying-geese\u2019 to China-centred \u2018Bamboo Capi- talism\u2019,\u201d CCIS Working Paper, No. 3, Center for Comparative Integration Studies, Aalborg University. Zebregs, H. (2004), \u201cIntraregional Trade in Emerging Asia,\u201d IMF Policy Discussion Paper, 04/1. 41 Annex A Flying geese framework: Its origin and extensions The FG framework was first introduced by Kaname Akamatsu in the 1930s, whereby he describes the de- velopment patterns in the Japanese industry by exploring the imports, domestic production, and exports of Japanese industries from 1868 to the years of World War II (See Box A.1). Akamatsu (1962) extends his analysis through two variants of the fundamental wild-geese flying pattern: the development of the industrial structure from less sophisticated goods to more sophisticated ones, and the development of relatively less advanced economies turning into advanced economies. This latter has been the central issue in the discus- sions on economic development within the framework of regional economic development. There are three strands of research in the literature, each of which extends Akamatsu\u2019s framework. While the first strand of these contributions discusses the framework within a theory of industrial develop- ment, the second reproduces Akamatsu\u2019s statistical analysis of the patterns, and pursues empirical testing of the framework. The last strand takes a critical view with respect to the validity or applicability of the FG pattern of development. Whether critical or not, this strand raises attention to the framework and underlines its importance to understanding the dynamic shifts in the regional division of labour. The following discussion prepares the groundwork to recast the FG pattern of development with a brief review of selected studies illustrating the three strands. Kojima (1960, 2000) focused on the international spread of the FG pattern as a policy framework. His most extended model of the FG pattern of development (Kojima model III, see Box A.2) has important impli- cations for the cooperative relations among Japan, first-tier countries, and second-tier countries, as well as China. He predicts that the region\u2019s FG framework type of development will spread to new members, such as Cambodia, Lao PDR, India, Pakistan, and Viet Nam, as well as the Democratic People\u2019s Republic (DPR) of Korea (Kojima 2002; 13). Kojima argues that for this to happen there is a vital need for the establishment of an Asian Economic Community (AEC), including the establishment of an Asian Monetary Fund, which should promote a \u201cfunctional regional integration.\u201d His definition of functional regional integration, however, goes beyond liberalization of trade and investment structure. Through integration, member economies can improve their industrial and production structure in terms of technological capacity as well as production and manage- ment systems. Trade liberalization is crucial to expanding trade within and outside the region, he argues, but this should not exclude nurturing infant industries by temporary protection. According to Kojima (2002), functional regional integration should bring not only economic benefits, but also improvements in political and social institutions to the whole region (p. 26). Only in this way will development in the region continue to spread successfully in line with the FG framework.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "44131ea1-8a12-4086-aaf6-85d0b5535f2f": {"__data__": {"id_": "44131ea1-8a12-4086-aaf6-85d0b5535f2f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5e94038a7083f887518f1abe0ed173bec1aa7d403c0114892dccaea670b08e1a"}, "2": {"node_id": "0d2195b3-3427-48ff-b3fe-f3b903d5007b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3f327751cc3a63178a915f177fd376a3b16b920ff0468afa5d13650f24117551"}}, "hash": "2fe2702ec2c737e4f56e71c1ef28450c7ef80356b36861467df69900cd20eedb", "text": "42 Box A.1 Akamatsu\u2019s wild-geese flying pattern Akamatsu (1962) sketches a wild-geese flying pattern of development based on the similarity of the import, production, and export curves to geese flying in an orderly rank, forming an inverse V as depicted in Figure A.1. Three main observations can be made from this figure: \uf06c In all industries there is a sequential order from imports to domestic production to exports. \uf06c The start of imports of crude goods precedes the time for the imports of refined goods; in other words, imports of capital goods come after the imports of consumer goods. \uf06c The import curve shows a decline with the rise in domestic production, and the export curve slopes down (sooner or later) when the industry matures, depending on the characteristics of the goods. Figure A.1 Wild-geese flying pattern Source: Figure 1 in Akamatsu (1962, p. 12). Based on these reflections, Akamatsu develops four historical stages for a single industry\u2019s evolution in a country: i.) importing phase; ii.) domestic production phase; iii.) exporting phase; and iv.) reverse-importing phase as the industry\u2019s production", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3ea01b56-b649-4200-93bb-1c9e36c1b578": {"__data__": {"id_": "3ea01b56-b649-4200-93bb-1c9e36c1b578", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "889912327c340e27fd48075da45e7eb4ba53570453caa0f0609491995083ac6e"}, "3": {"node_id": "45bd1d1f-2a18-44f9-87ee-5018671e60d1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "dbd91aa768d8fe043e8b6245d2fd8e2c7aa704e8156c381108a5453d0159d607"}}, "hash": "df5917ff6b1b011cbbe387b1e7baf071094f8aeac496ee6691301ecf5d62109a", "text": "moves out of the national boundaries, i.e., when a country begins to import that industry\u2019s products as production moves to other countries, while its domestic industry advances toward the production of more sophisticated products. Akamatsu also formulates a modified version of the single industry development into a regional development type. He describes the historical pattern of economic growth in developing countries similar to the historical stages of an industry. In the modified version of Akamatsu\u2019s framework, the first stage corresponds to the phase during which a developing country imports manufactured goods from advanced countries in exchange for raw materials. The second stage consists of the rise of the domestic production of the imported consumer goods. The third stage refers to the phase when the domestic sector turns into an export sector. The fourth and last stage stands for the emergence of capital goods\u2019 production in the domestic market as well as reverses in the importing of consumer goods. 43 Box A.2 Kojima\u2019s FDI-led FG pattern of development Kojima introduces three theoretical pillars for the FG pattern. The first pillar refers to industrial upgrading, which is based on the accumulation of capital. This he calls Kojima model I: industrial upgrading from labour- intensive to labour-saving industries stimulated by technological progress and rapid accumulation of capital via a high savings ratio. The second pillar puts emphasis on industrial upgrading through FDI, assuming that FDI is pro-trade in his terms. Trade-oriented FDI refers to the flows from comparatively disadvantaged indus- tries in the investing country into comparatively advantaged industries of the host country (Kojima 2000, p. 383). He also discusses the spillover effects created by FDI and possible backward and forward linkages that contribute to the host economy supporting their climb up the development ladder. More specific to the regional extension of the FG pattern, Kojima (2000, p. 386-388) introduces a third model: Kojima model III \u2014 a theory of agreed specialization, which puts particular emphasis on the post- homogenization stage of the economies in order to induce relief from trading wars. The basis of his argu- ment is the need for intra-industry trade promotion when the trade and production structure of integrated economies become quite similar. At this point de facto agreed specialization can be observed within firms; and Kojima suggests that trade and investment activities can be pursued under such agreed specialization. Rising China and India: Are geese still flying? In contrast to the positive view of Asian regional development provided by Kojima (2002), given the recent dynamics in the region, questions have been raised about whether the geese are still flying.26 Emerging China and India, with their particular economic structures, are at the center of the discussion. A growing number of studies have suggested the FG view of the regional economies should instead be characterized as \u201csitting ducks\u201d (Ahearne et al. 2006). China\u2019s huge pool of cheap labour and the undervaluation of its currency rela- tive to other economies in the region form the basis for this view. Thus, there are now two opposing views: While some studies present empirical evidence consistent with the FG pattern (Rose 2007; Kwan 2002), others discuss a shifting pattern from a Japan-led to a China-centered formation (Xing 2007). Ahearne et al. (2006) argue that the two polar views do not do justice to the rapidly evolving trade relationships among Asian economies (p. 2). The authors suggest that Chinese export growth and other Asian economies move together. They both depend on common shocks, confirming the relative importance of foreign income, along with exchange rates, in the determination of export growth. Ahearne et al. also argue that recent dramatic changes in trade shares are consistent with the FG pattern, i.e., a pattern in which China moves into the product space vacated by the first-tier economies, with greater integration of trade across the region in production networks. Evidence of China gaining market share across the globe despite the declining share of other Asian economies is in line with what the second-tier countries experienced earlier on, when they took their place in a number of industries at the expense of the first-tier. Thus, rather than indicating a disruption, Ahearne et al. accept the second view and lay the groundwork for a FG-consistent pattern of Asian development (p. 3).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "45bd1d1f-2a18-44f9-87ee-5018671e60d1": {"__data__": {"id_": "45bd1d1f-2a18-44f9-87ee-5018671e60d1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "889912327c340e27fd48075da45e7eb4ba53570453caa0f0609491995083ac6e"}, "2": {"node_id": "3ea01b56-b649-4200-93bb-1c9e36c1b578", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "df5917ff6b1b011cbbe387b1e7baf071094f8aeac496ee6691301ecf5d62109a"}}, "hash": "dbd91aa768d8fe043e8b6245d2fd8e2c7aa704e8156c381108a5453d0159d607", "text": "3). A similar point on the possible benefits of recent developments is made for the impact of China\u2019s im- mense growth on the rest of the region. The argument that Japan\u2019s recent recovery from of its long economic crisis due to the sheer size of its exports to China is also used as supporting evidence for the existing FG", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ba69481a-a088-4c16-b119-825863b9400f": {"__data__": {"id_": "ba69481a-a088-4c16-b119-825863b9400f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "49db73519cb7aea93bc40396bfca6e18b6458bfb67c09e0c2dbc19c557279cc3"}, "3": {"node_id": "5a7f56aa-44c4-4845-910e-322fcc269f6f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0f3ca259418f80c7b3cfe0825387d642139062afb3ea51173402b3db1e98fd22"}}, "hash": "3e5667c14e6a5749011d3c560787cf95e319146ed177f608c9b2609ef995eb24", "text": "pattern (Xing 2007). Whether or not the rise of China is a zero-sum game depends on whether one looks at the outcome of the FG pattern over a short-term or long-term time span. For instance, Holst and Weiss (2004) raise attention to the rivalry between ASEAN countries and China in the short-run. On the other hand, others point out the possible opportunities for economic growth in the long-term, if the necessary steps are taken at the policy level (Batra 2006; Holst and Weiss 2004; Tambunan 2006; De Castro 2006). 26 For more extensive discussions on the issue, please refer to Kwan (2002), Ahearne et al. (2006), and Rose (1997). 44 Flying geese critique The validity of the FG framework of development has been criticized at two different levels, one empirical and the other theoretical. Empirical contributions commonly share the argument that FG model predictions do not materialize in all cases. For instance, Bernard and Ravenhill (1995) argue that manufacturing exports in Southeast Asia emerged without passing through import-substitution industrialization, unlike what hap- pened in the Republic of Korea and Taiwan (PoC). In addition, they show that the reverse importing phase has not been observed in Japan, despite FG predictions. Using as an illustration the production networks in the microelectronics industry as well as the simultaneous boom within the sector across the region, they assert that any research on the recent developments and changes in production relations within the region should focus on production networks, particularly on the relations and linkages between states and local and transnational firms. Similarly, Tung (2003) analyzes international fragmentation of production and product differentiation against the validity of the FG pattern. More specifically, Tung points out that the FG framework does not hold in specific industries when analyzed at the disaggregated level; the electronics industry is one such example. However, we should mention that Kojima (2000) counter-argued these points, demonstrating that Tung and others are incorrectly identifying the FG pattern with the product-cycle theory. Ginzburg and Simonazzi (2005) cite different reasons why the FG pattern fails to explain developments in the electronics sector. They present: a.) the declining ratio of value added that retains from exports within the country, and b.) motivations to lower the costs of pollution created by industries in advanced countries as the determining factors behind FDI flows, rather than FG motivations. They introduce a different reformula- tion of the framework whereby the delocalization of different stages of production across national boundaries is prominent. At the theoretical level, the FG framework has been criticized by its inability to explain the complexities of the structure of the production linkages and their transformation in Asia. Bernard and Ravenhill (1995) call the recent attempts on FG modeling at best a gross oversimplification of the interrelated complications of an industrial development process. The FG model, they argue, is an ahistoric description of the transformations in production, such as the flow of a single commodity from one place to another, isolated from all other changes. Each country experiences the industrialization process at a different historical time under differ- ent social, political, institutional, and economic conditions, which should be included in any analysis of the regional hierarchy among different countries. Similarly, Amsden (1991) argues that development cannot be just based upon a regional division of labour with regional externalities. Rather, there is a need to explore the late industrializers\u2019 development through a general institutional model covering a theory of the specific conditions for specific cases. Amsden also questions the validity of the FG framework, suggesting the Latin American region as a counter example to such a model. The fact that the Latin American experience is characterized by less dynamic FDI coming in the form of subsidiaries from the United States is one reason why the FG framework cannot explain the in- dustrial development in that region. This nature of FDI, as argued, reinforces the bias towards inward-looking industrialization without improving international competitiveness.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5a7f56aa-44c4-4845-910e-322fcc269f6f": {"__data__": {"id_": "5a7f56aa-44c4-4845-910e-322fcc269f6f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "49db73519cb7aea93bc40396bfca6e18b6458bfb67c09e0c2dbc19c557279cc3"}, "2": {"node_id": "ba69481a-a088-4c16-b119-825863b9400f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3e5667c14e6a5749011d3c560787cf95e319146ed177f608c9b2609ef995eb24"}}, "hash": "0f3ca259418f80c7b3cfe0825387d642139062afb3ea51173402b3db1e98fd22", "text": "It is important to emphasize at this point that a FG framework does not encompass only a harmoni- ous movement of sectors from less comparative advantage areas to others, recently termed as \u201crecycling of comparative advantage\u201d; rather, it has a dimension of conflict by which \u201c\u2026local producers find themselves in a death struggle against imports and \u2018pour their hearts\u2019 into copying foreign goods and inventing new ones to win the upper hand over imports\u2026\u201d (Rowthorn 1996: p. 38). One should keep in mind that investment is pursued by firms, not by governments, and that a transnational company (TNC) seeks to invest in the South when in pursuit of higher profits, given the high capital accumulation", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ba6615ed-aa6a-4aac-9e26-ec1522c9d387": {"__data__": {"id_": "ba6615ed-aa6a-4aac-9e26-ec1522c9d387", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "T