and lower ones are exported more by low-income countries, a product sophistication index (SP) is calculated for each product (i) exported across the globe. This index uses the shares of each country (j) in global exports, calculated as the ratio of total exported value of a product (i) in country (j) (Xij) to the total value of world exports of that product (Xi) while taking the weighted average of these shares using GDP per capita (Yj) of each exporting country as weights: (1) Step 2: Assuming that the higher the advancement level of the export structure of a country the higher the share of highly sophisticated products (i.e., high-technology, high value-added manufacturing goods), a country sophistication index for country (j), SCj is the share of each country\u2019s manufactured exports (Xj i) in total global manufactured exports (Xj) as weighted by SPi: (2) This allows us to compare the index level of each country, which corresponds to the mean of the distri- bution of sophistication indices of all exported products. We followed Kwan\u2019s (2002) calculation for the most part, but our indices carry some differences, as follows: \uf06c Kwan uses US imports as a proxy for world exports. In this paper we use countries\u2019 exports to the world to calculate SPi and SPj because US imports do not constitute a good proxy for total exports for some of the countries in the region. 50 \uf06c In terms of GDP per capita, we use per capita GDP at purchasing power parity (PPP) rather than the nomi- nal values. Significance of the GDP levels of exporting countries in determining SPi reveals the implica- tions of using a price-adjusted measure. Since per capita GDP (PPP) provides a standard separated from price disparities of the same product, we believe this prevents any variation in SPi caused by differences in the price of corresponding goods in different countries. Since these price disparities are observed more in non-tradable sectors, excluding them by using PPP is crucial, as our study covers trade-related sectors. \uf06c Kwan calculates SPi by repeating Step 1 (above) for each year covered in his analysis. Thus, the resulting index for each product is not fixed over time. In that case, when the exporting country\u2019s share stays the same between two consecutive periods we might still observe shifts in the distribution structure due to the changes in the performance of the exporting economies.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "432b794c-d3d8-42da-830b-e0d538b33efd": {"__data__": {"id_": "432b794c-d3d8-42da-830b-e0d538b33efd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ab4f632137e6cb882f9fef383c79cb80fc9128fef2abc281387c7106c0c88b76"}, "2": {"node_id": "12c88077-610f-4a36-9d44-13f5dbafbfa1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "dc04b763b278e7db7814a77dbdfce9a6a67825ad8bc252bb51d1df74645a63a2"}}, "hash": "5b1925883fba534354aa1df252eb9467142ca4f9a3731b40e22893fd13e47bcb", "text": "In other words, a comparison of distribu- tion of the sophistication indices between two points in time might, on one hand, reflect the changes in the export structure of an economy and, on the other hand, reflect the changes in the GDP levels of the main exporting economies if the GDP of different years are used. Thus, changes in GDPs over time can make a significant difference in the advancement level of the exports and, accordingly, the economy. Let us explain the underlying logic behind our third modification with an example. Suppose we would like to compare the distribution of export sophistication indices for country A in 2000 and 2005. Assume that country A\u2019s cumulative GDP growth rate adds up to 20 percent over the six years but that export shares for all goods stay the same. Under these assumptions the resulting distribution for Country A is expected to shift to the right, keeping", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7250f79e-e1c1-4eea-a722-0fc4103d6e56": {"__data__": {"id_": "7250f79e-e1c1-4eea-a722-0fc4103d6e56", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "The Potential for Cooperative Regional Industrial Development Strategies in Asia and the Implications of Emerging China and India", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-cooperative-regional-industrial-development-strategies-asia-and-implications-emerging-china-and-india", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ba424157c553d76c49d1932bdaea1930fe0d60a02f14b53f7408f5ea2cdd5e51"}}, "hash": "ba424157c553d76c49d1932bdaea1930fe0d60a02f14b53f7408f5ea2cdd5e51", "text": "its earlier shape since the export shares of the goods have not changed. This shift might be considered a structural shift in exports in terms of the advancement level of products, leading us to think that it is an FG-consistent shift; and, in fact, this might be true as long as GDP growth reflects the changes in the sophistication level of exports. However, GDP growth might overestimate the implications of any struc- tural shift. On rather different grounds, both shifts can be argued as significant indicators of a FG framework. Nevertheless, a decomposition of each effect on the indices is required in order to understand better the underlying dynamics. For this reason, in our second step calculations we, unlike Kwan, include the calculated for a single year \u2014 not for each year \u2014 and use it as a proxy for the average of sophistication indices of the exported goods over the period of analysis. Because we present snapshot descriptions over a 10-year period, the mid-year\u2019s indices best serves for our purpose. It is possible to argue that growth performance over time comprises one important aspect of the FG pattern of development, yet our indices will not include them due to the reasons explained above. This is the limitation and the scope of the empirical methods introduced in this paper. Pros and cons of sophistication indices As any other summary statistic, the method we use has both pros and cons. First, unlike the current industry classification standards, which limit the sophistication content of products into a limited number of groups, the sophistication index enables us to analyze the product characteristics in a wider range with relative or- dering of each product. The sophistication index removes the binary characterization of technology-based classifications. It also has the advantage of providing unique continuous scores for each product at any level, involving a quite detailed range of products. Second, analyzing the product characteristics based on the average income of exporting economies captures more than just technical characteristics. Product sophistication goes beyond \u201cfactor intensity com- parisons\u201d proposed by the conventional international trade theory as a major theoretical pillar. Factors such as differentiation, susceptibility to fragmention of the process of production, resource availability, and others are also important in terms of trade performance, as mentioned by Lall, Weiss, and Zhang (2006). The sophistica- tion index contains more information in this respect compared to conventional measures. 51 Third, there exists a recent finding on the close correlation between the quality of export products and growth performance (Hausman et al. 2006). This shows that sophistication indices, by measuring the quality of exports, can predict subsequent economic growth, which has important implications in terms of the FG pattern of development, which is at the centre of the current study. With respect to the shortcomings of our method: first, unlike RCA, SP does not provide information about relative specialization of an economy\u2019s export structure. Second, as with any other one-dimensional index, it is not possible to disentangle the structural shifts in exports unless it is reflected in the level of sophis- tication; i.e., moving from textiles to low-tech machinery exports that have similar SPs may not be captured. If possible, a multidimensional sophistication index might preclude any such potential drawbacks, and the points raised here partly lay the groundwork for recommendations for further research presented in the last section of this paper. Asia Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative UNDP Regional Centre for Asia Pacific Colombo Office 23 Independence Avenue Colombo 7 Sri Lanka Tel: +94 11 4526400 Fax: +94 11 4526410 Email: rcc@undp.org Website: http://www.undprcc.lk", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dfbf8a93-ecfa-4f49-98da-8b522ddeca3d": {"__data__": {"id_": "dfbf8a93-ecfa-4f49-98da-8b522ddeca3d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Toward Export Diversification: Trade and Industrial Policy Environment in Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4f9c8e023a101ce84a2a47e6fae86dd4d7dc5e62b56995d69845f7862ebbf0a6"}, "3": {"node_id": "5dca5a9d-3e32-4d8a-ab38-aff307c7765a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cf0ad323b3f05ffdbc3c95083d9fbfc9fca3b14e4011c8dbdca409e90483f217"}}, "hash": "ab8fa1cacbf44e68bba5be5fb5a384351f5c1036d225dfd016d2c61dbb52e008", "text": "Toward Export Diversification: Trade and Industrial Policy Environment in Asian LDCs Joint Policy Brief Issue 2- June 2008 Economic Institute of Cambodia and UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo [Asia-Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative] \"\"'- ~~- , -.- -'\\.\" ::::0: \u2022 _ , = - -~'~\\~'. - ._ \" ic - ' -.. - ~ -) - -!. ,.....s. ... When countries enter into export-driven industrialization, often the first commodities they produce are labour-intensive, non-durable products, such as textiles and garments. Lack offoreign exchange and access to credit can limit the volume of industrial capitals in the countries. A large reserve army of labour contributes to keep the average wage level low. Growth of the labour-intensive sectors has been a stepping stone towards economic development in Asia as the success cases of East and Southeast Asian countries illustrate. Some Asian LDCs have already joined this development path. Labour-intensive sectors such as ready-made garments have been providing a regular income to millions, especially women with no or little education, who would otherwise still be excluded from participating in income-generating activities. Many of them send part of their income to their families in rural areas. A majority of the remittances are used to purchase of basic necessities and agricultural inputs, for education fees for siblings, and repayment of debts by their families. Although remittances from migrants in abroad have been regarded by some as a key to poverty reduction, job creation in home countries brings other benefits. For example, the indirect jobs are also created near the factories as the demand for housing, services, dining, and transportation arises with the number of manufacutring jobs created. With the end of quota-based trade on textiles and clothing, the LDC exporters of these products are in need of export diversification so as to reduce the negative impacts generated by trade liberalization, if any. Diversification also has a positive impact on the economic growth. A cross-country study shows that export diversification is positively associated with the growth in per capita GDP (Raihan 2007). Diversification of industry portfolios that leads to job growth should be of particular interest to countries where there is a high demand for job creation. Prospects for export diversification A series of studies in Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR and Nepal, commissioned by UNDP, have identified the production of specific goods and services, which will not only enhance export potential but which will also have high human development benefits. Selection of sectors were based on the following criteria: revealed comparative advantage; export prospects and their sustainability; use of local inputs; and potential for creating employment, particularly for women and other disadvantaged segments of the society. Use of local inputs is important for creating backward linkages and higher value-added in the economy. Employment creation, especially in rural areas, is crucial in the view of human development and sustainable development. The selected sectors which are common among these four countries are food processing, handicrafts, herbs and herbal products, and tourism. www.undprcc.lk 1 Toward Export Diversification Given their richness in biodiversity and the climatic conditions, these countries have a great potential for producing high-value added products such as organic products and herbal extracts or medicinal plants. Cultural diversity in these countries also provides an enriched variety of handicrafts in materials and design. Many of these products are unique to their locality and may be eligible for Geographical Indication protection, which can result in higher premiums to producers. Having a number of the World Heritage sites, national parks and cultural heritage, these countries have a great potential to pursue tourism for sustainable development. Tourism can also provide markets for handicrafts and processed food as souvenirs or to be consumed at hotels and restaurants. For better industrial policy environment: Issues and policy options for Asian LDCs One of the main factors in determining the prospect of increased exports as well as investment from both domestic and foreign investors is the socio-economic environment that influences returns from investment. Macro-economic instability, poor infra structural facilities, and deteriorating law and order are a few examples, which can hamper the profitability of investment. Better trade and an improved industrial policy environment for businesses, especially for small and medium enterprises (SMEs) in rural areas, is essential to export diversification for sustainable development.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5dca5a9d-3e32-4d8a-ab38-aff307c7765a": {"__data__": {"id_": "5dca5a9d-3e32-4d8a-ab38-aff307c7765a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Toward Export Diversification: Trade and Industrial Policy Environment in Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4f9c8e023a101ce84a2a47e6fae86dd4d7dc5e62b56995d69845f7862ebbf0a6"}, "2": {"node_id": "dfbf8a93-ecfa-4f49-98da-8b522ddeca3d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ab8fa1cacbf44e68bba5be5fb5a384351f5c1036d225dfd016d2c61dbb52e008"}}, "hash": "cf0ad323b3f05ffdbc3c95083d9fbfc9fca3b14e4011c8dbdca409e90483f217", "text": "Major structural barriers and supply-side constraints need to be removed. Common supply-side constraints which Bangladesh, Cambodia, Nepal, and Lao PDR have thus far confronted are; lack of access to finance; poor infrastructure; lack of trade facilitation measures; shortage of skilled workers; and lack of standards and certifications. Issues as well as policy suggestions will be summarized below. Enhancing access to finance", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4fda8fcc-13c7-471f-bcfc-e15ef7bae8a4": {"__data__": {"id_": "4fda8fcc-13c7-471f-bcfc-e15ef7bae8a4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Toward Export Diversification: Trade and Industrial Policy Environment in Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "79596d017f109296e77e637703668a1b668500afebb42c4922dbc15c89d44aaf"}}, "hash": "79596d017f109296e77e637703668a1b668500afebb42c4922dbc15c89d44aaf", "text": "Access to credit has been identified as a critical factor affecting business operation and expansion in these four countries. Lack of access to finance also hinders the prospect of accessing better technology, which may eventually result in reduced productivities of firms and industries. The problem is severe particularly for the SMEs, including those in the export-oriented Issue 2 June 2008 sectors. High interest rates and a lack of collateral in the form of land and buildings for advancing loans are found to be bottlenecks for SMEs trying to access formal credit channels. Banks are hesitant or unwilling to lend to SMEs as they do not consider them to be attractive and profitable undertakings. A number of micro-finance institutions (MFls) have provided small loans to SMEs and farmers but their interest rates are often higher than commercial banks partly due to the high operation costs of MFls. In the case of Cambodia, the interest rates charged by MFls are 3-3.5 percent per month - very high by international standards and relative to business profitability in rural areas (EIC 2007). Most MFls have failed to raise resources locally; as a result, MFls depend on funding from overseas banks. An increase in local saving and deposits for MFls is crucial for the sustainable financing of small enterprises in Cambodia. Promotion of savings and deposit accounts and diversification of saving and deposit options are possible tools to increase local funding at MFls. SME's enhanced access to loans from commercial banks should be achieved. Development of an effective SME financial reporting system and a credit information sharing system can assist the goal. Sound monetary policy is a key for the LDCs to keep inflation rate - and thus interest rates - low. Better infrastructure Weak physical infrastructure appears to plague trade and industrial development in Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR and Nepal. Proper infrastructure and reliable services are vital for connecting all the players along the value chain and ensuring a smooth delivery of the final goods to the markets. Investment in roads, railways, waterways, ports, telecommunications and basic utility services such as electricity and water will assist industries to improve their competitiveness by cutting lead time and production costs. A survey shows that utilities account for significant share of the total production costs of the manufactured goods (EIC 2007). The recent fuel price hike is likely to diminish cost competitiveness further at various stages of the value chain, such as processing ---------------------- www.undprcc.lk 2 Toward Export Diversification and transportation, in these cou ntries. In addition to enhanced access to services, supply of reliable services is vital as power interruptions and quality of telecommunications are serious problems in LDCs. Maintenance of the existing infrastructure should also be strengthened. Private sector participation into this investment can be yet other effective policy measures. Improved trade facilitation measures Cumbersome administrative procedures and requirement of trade documentation by government agencies increase the cost of doing business significantly and weaken the competitiveness of the exporting firms. These obstacles take various form s. such as licensing, inspection and customs regulations. Table 1 compares the costs and procedures involved in trade for selected Asian countries with the sub-regional average. Lao PDR and Nepal, both landlocked LDCs, perform poorly in all categories compared to the sub-regional average, particularly in the costs and time involved in trade. For example, the time and cost required in Lao PDR to export and import goods are double the sub-regional average. Cambodia seems competitive in terms of costs of export or import procedures, but more documents and time are required to complete trade procedures than in neighboring countries, e.g., Viet Nam. In most of categories, Bangladesh is performing better than the sub-regional average. However, in comparison with a competitor in the region, Bangladesh is lagging behind the India - its biggest competitor in the region - in number of days required for export and import. Issue 2 June 2008 Reforms in the government administration in trade matters, licensing, and custom procedures are needed urgently to improve trade facilitation in these LDCs. Involvement of all stakeholders, including the private sector, in this process is a key to success. Investment in human development Despite having an abundance of labour, a shortage of skilled workers is a major constraint in the new startup and expansion of the manufacturing and service sectors in many LDC s. When export diversification and increased backward linkages are of high priority, as in the cases of the LDCs under consideration, such goals can be preconditioned by the limited availability of a skilled workforce in all levels ranging from management to specialized work. A certain level", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2943a44f-31af-49e8-8d13-93abb772abc4": {"__data__": {"id_": "2943a44f-31af-49e8-8d13-93abb772abc4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Toward Export Diversification: Trade and Industrial Policy Environment in Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6e8bd0b988d4cfe9103a41f8ad0e4427688724ac97440e531a0807e5df49630d"}, "3": {"node_id": "6adbda70-b28f-4fe8-b777-bc0d1f6db694", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial-policy-environment-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-2", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8b6c6552f0079e3d7043e5ae0cb5d76956b606436f28ab1cf4393792e9f1b193"}}, "hash": "28f7cc0aa05b68d081f1a7f22bad0dfd1e85ed58d68dad2070495453a69083b5", "text": "of formal educational attainment and job-specific training and experience are essential for skill formation. Therefore, both quality general education and vocational and technical training suitable to the export diversification needs are required. While the improvements in the standard of education may require long-term planning and investment, various short- to medium-term vocational and technical training programmers can be provided through public-private partnerships. Empowerment of rural populations, women and other disadvantaged segments of the society involved in the production of exportable goods and services is also indispensable for sustainable development. Table 1 The costs and procedures involved in trade. Region or Documents Time for Cost to Documents nmefor Cost to Economy for export export export for import import import (number) (days) (U5S pe, (number) (days) (U5S pe, container) container) E. Asia & Pacific 6.9 24.5 885 7.5 25.8 1,015 Cambodia 11 37 722 11 46 852 Lao PDR 9 50 1.750 10 50 1.930 Viet Nam 6 24 669 8 23 881 South Asia 8.6 32.5 1,180 9.1 32.1 1,418 Bangladesh 7 28 844 9 32 1,148 Nepal 9 43 1,600 10 35 1,725 India 8 18 820 9 21 910 Source: World Bank. 2008. -------------------- www.undprcc.lk 3 Toward Export Diversification Standards and certifications Sales of organic food and textiles, herbs and herbal products, and cultural products such as handicrafts have expanded rapidly, especially in the markets of industrialized countries. Many producers are supplying the increasing competitive markets. Certification or designation as environmentally-friendly products or fair-traded goods is seen as means to create a niche market and add premium to such products. Standards and certification are useful measures to ensure the quality of goods and services. However, these system as well as other measures such as sanitary and phytosanitary (SPS) measu res can become barriers in exports when lDCs cannot meet requirements for international standards. To overcome these issues, technical and financial assistance should be provided in these LDCs so that producers and service providers, especially SMEs, are well informed about standards and certification processes and manage the quality assurance. The capacity of certifying agencies should be enhanced as well. For products, which are derived from, or use local or indigenous knowledge in the production, the intellectual property over such knowledge may be an issue. This may be the case where products are sold without benefits accruing to the communities or groups that have supplied the local or indigenous knowledge. A mechanism that formally involves all legitimate stakeholders including community knowledge holders should be established to develop relevant policies and laws on intellectual property rights, biodiversity, and protection of local knowledge. In the case of products such as herbs, herbal med icines, and medicinal plants, there is also a need to expand the rights of local communities over forest resources management to maximize benefits for local harvesters and minimize illegal collection of resources. The studies of Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR and Nepal have identified a number of sectors with significant export potential. Even at their currently underdeveloped status, these sectors are contributing Issue 2 June 2008 to export earnings and generating employment opportunities in LDCs. Further development and expansion of these sectors, therefore, is likely to have a considerable positive impact on employment creation, poverty alleviation and human development. Though the country experiences suggest that there have been some efforts in providing assistance to the development of the labour-intensive sectors, a number of critical constraints continue to hinder the goal of export diversification. The respective governments and private sectors need to make concerted efforts to overcome these constraints. References Economic Institute of Cambodia (EIC). 2007. Export Diversification and Value Addition for Human Development. Phnom Penh: EIC. www.eicambodia.org Raihan, Selim, Ratnakar Adhikari and Kamalesh Adhikari (eds.). 2007. Export Diversification for Human Development in the Post-ATC Era: Perspectives from Asian LOes. Colombo: UNDP RCC. http://www.undprcc.lkJPublicationsfTRADE/Export_ Diversification.pdf Raihan, Selim. 2007.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6adbda70-b28f-4fe8-b777-bc0d1f6db694": {"__data__": {"id_": "6adbda70-b28f-4fe8-b777-bc0d1f6db694", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/toward-export-diversification-trade-and-industrial