 null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "412a9a7f25304b7ac57498e45b6f21d7ca460ccbe2adb652bee2070d43bb5c15"}}, "hash": "412a9a7f25304b7ac57498e45b6f21d7ca460ccbe2adb652bee2070d43bb5c15", "text": "and accounting, hotels and architecture, to audio-visuals, education, health and construction. The volume of economic activities in these sectors is huge: More than 60 percent of the world\u2019s gross output is accounted for by value-addition in services. Yet because many of these activities were deemed \u201cuntradable\u201d until recently, the share of services in global trade is only around 20 percent,1 with exports valued at about US$ 1.57 trillion. With the advent of new transmission technologies, improved means of transportation and reorientation in priorities of states away from direct control and management of many commercial activities, both the perception and reality of the tradability of services has increased in the past two decades. Since 1980, trade in services has grown faster than trade in goods, despite the former being subjected to complex non-tariff barriers (WTO 2003, 9). Because of the possibilities created by IT- enabled technologies, some forms of trade in services no longer require a simultaneous presence of both the producer and consumer, which used to be one of the distinguishing characteristics of this trade. With the formal entry into force of the binding General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS) at the WTO, and commencement of multilateral negotiations in 2000, the role of trade in services in development has become prominent. 1This could be an understatement, since not all services activities are captured in formal balance-of-payments statements. For discussion on problems of collecting accurate services data, see Raghavan (2004). Even when available, they may not be sufficiently disaggregated. There is a particular lack of internationally comparable statistics on South- South services trade. 8 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All The stakes are thus high, not only because services include sectors that are the drivers of modern economic growth, with great potential for generating jobs and incomes, but because they also include sectors where commercial motivations are secondary to the prime human development objective of ensuring basic well-being through decent health, education, energy, and water and sanitation supplies, among others. In fact, the share of services in GDP in countries systematically correlates with levels of per-capita income. In developed countries, such a share typically exceeds 70 percent of national output (73 percent in the United States), while in developing countries, it is around 50 percent (lower in the Least Developed Countries, such as only 25 percent in Lao PDR). Until the end of 1970s, there was a tendency to downplay the role of services in development. It was assumed that growth in services was an outcome of an enlarged development process, mostly sustained by industrial activities, and that as countries entered the post-industrial period, shifts would occur automatically to the services sector. Seen as an offshoot of progress elsewhere, countries did not even find it necessary to have distinct strategies on services (Gibbs and Ognivtsev 2004, 7). It is only since the mid-1980s that the view on the two-way causal relationship between services and economic development has been increasingly accepted. As people\u2019s needs grow, and public institutions in developing countries come under great strain in their attempts to cope with increasing claims on resources, they are compelled to explore a range of options to fill glaring gaps: increase in domestic resource mobilisation for public investments in infrastructure, recourse to overseas transfers, grants and loans, and international trade. Trade in services is additionally crucial because it almost subsumes the hugely important subject of investment under the logic that services can be provided through \u201ccommercial presence\u201d in a foreign market by owners of capital belonging elsewhere. This phenomenon had become so pronounced by the turn of the century that services accounted for more than 60 percent (or US$ 500 billion) of total FDI inflows during 2001- 9 2002. While in the early years finance constituted most of the trade in services, energy, water and telecommunications are now receiving increasing attention; between 1990 and 2002, the value of FDI stock in electric power generation and distribution rose by a factor of 14 (WIR 2004, xx-xxi). In the specific service sectors that are the subject of this paper, the challenge of ensuring universal and affordable access to health, water, sanitation and energy for poor people remains an utmost priority of most national governments. International trade in these services is not, and will never be, a substitute for conscious national strategies aimed at meeting universal goals in favour of poor people. The provision of most essential services is almost entirely a public prerogative, not only because of their strong human rights content, but also because of the large social externalities and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "eda811a8-f567-4146-90b5-53a63e4eea6f": {"__data__": {"id_": "eda811a8-f567-4146-90b5-53a63e4eea6f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Progra