he scope of the agreement is sweeping, and proposals on the table in Geneva can in theory cover any service, in any sector, except those \u201csupplied in the exercise of governmental authority.\u201d Article 1.3(c) explains that this means any service that is supplied neither on a commercial basis nor in competition with one or more service suppliers.3 While GATS does not require privatisation or liberalisation, and governments can choose to make no commitments, or schedule limitations on market access and national treatment when commitments are made, the overall purpose of the agreement is clear. Through \u201cprogressive liberalisation,\u201d it is to eventually achieve for trade in services what GATT has achieved so far for trade in goods. A first-ever agreement of legally enforceable rules, GATS draws on GATT principles (such as national treatment), but places them in a different context; at the same time, it extends the scope to measures affecting issues as diverse as FDI flows, qualification of professionals, and movement of data as well as people across borders as service providers (Gibbs and Ognivtsev 2004, 8). To date, with the exception of countries or territories that acceded to the WTO after 2001 (namely, China, Cambodia, Nepal and Taiwan Province of China), not many Asia-Pacific countries have undertaken notable commitments. Worldwide, no member has made a commitment at the WTO on water distribution.4 With some developed countries realising that the flexible \u201crequest-offer\u201d approach of GATS negotiations is not opening up foreign markets fast or deep enough, new proposals can be expected in the future that will seek to pressure and expedite opening of 3 Commercial basis means that there is a notion of profit seeking involved; competition means two or more service providers target the same market with substitutable products. 4 Further, only 24 developing countries have made commitments on hospital services, while 12 developing countries have made commitments on primary education. These contrast with commitments made by WTO members in tourism (90 percent) or financial services (70 percent). 11 \u201ccore critical areas\u201d in developing countries.5 Thus, much of the controversy on GATS appears to be not about its present form and outcomes, but about what the agreement may evolve into (World Bank 2004, 105). It is against this background of stark human development needs, compelling public investment challenges, recent trends in trade in services and the political-economic realities surrounding international trade regimes that this paper is written, primarily for constituencies in Asia-Pacific. The most important motivation behind selecting trade in energy and environmental services is to see to what extent aspects of this trade can contribute to, or upset, the pursuit of human well-being aimed at ensuring universal access to and affordability of essential services by poor people. After detailing the scale of human development challenges in the two sectors, the paper recognises that these sectors also happen to be \u201cbig businesses\u201d with potential benefits in terms of employment, technology transfer and economic growth. In the two sectors, the paper briefly outlines the nature and scope of reforms, including attempts at deregulation and attachment of social obligations and welfare conditions. With empirical as well as anecdotal references to past experiences within Asia-Pacific and other regions, certain policy lessons are drawn, with the caveat that there can be no application of uniform policy across the diverse countries of Asia-Pacific. The two main sections conclude with suggested approaches", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "85f54b6a-e738-45d3-8d7e-37eac088e50b": {"__data__": {"id_": "85f54b6a-e738-45d3-8d7e-37eac088e50b", "embedding": null, "meta