 measures aimed at ensuring access to essential services by the poor are bolstered, not restrained. One framework that will be referred to repeatedly in this paper is the \u201cfour modes of service supply.\u201d First articulated by the UNCTAD Secretariat in the 1980s, this went on to lay the intellectual basis for the incorporation of the idea in all discourses on trade in services. The four modes of supply through which services can be traded are: Box 1: The Four Modes Mode 1: Cross-border supply \u2013 User in one country receives service from a provider abroad (e.g., IT-enabled medical diagnostics and advice, online energy trading and brokering) Mode 2: Consumption abroad \u2013 User moves abroad to consume a service (e.g., tourists, health patients) Mode 3: Commercial presence \u2013 User is offered service by entities owned by foreign providers (e.g., foreign-owned subsidiary in insurance, sanitation or electricity) Mode 4: Movement of natural persons \u2013 Service provider moves abroad to supply a service (e.g., nurses, construction workers). 13 II. International trade in environmental services and human development The scale of development challenges In the broadest sense, development is about improving the quality of life. The well-being of millions of people still living in absolute poverty in Asia-Pacific depends in part on a wide range of environmental resources, including access to and use of fresh drinking water and sanitation. Close to 2 billion people in Asia lack access to basic sanitation, and more than 650 million have no safe drinking water (WSSCC 2004, 28). The Pacific Island countries are three orders of magnitude smaller in size and population than Asia, but they share the same intensity of environmental problems. Child mortality is widely, uniformly and accurately reported across countries and is therefore a reliable indicator of national environmental health.6 Every day, 3,900 children worldwide die of diseases associated with water and sanitation, which are easily preventable. Almost half the people in the developing world have one or more diseases or infections associated with inadequate water supply and sanitation, like diarrhoea, intestinal helminth infections and dracunculiasis. According to The Lancet (2005, vol. 365), schistosomiasis afflicts 160 million people in the world, which basic sanitation can reduce by 77 percent; similarly, of the 6 million people who are blind because of trachoma, a preventable disease, improved access to water could reduce morbidity by 27 percent. Collectively, these amount to a colossal drain of human potential. The link between health and environmental problems is direct, especially in ever-growing urban settlements. In Pakistan, 40 percent of infant mortality is due to water pollution; in Bangkok, half the city 6 Future research on environmental indices should focus on establishing datasets of child death rates from proximate environmental causes, intestinal infections and respiratory diseases. Statistics for access to safe water and basic sanitation are considered less reliable. 14 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All suffers from air pollution-induced respiratory illnesses. In China, two- thirds of its major cities are seriously short of water, with 700 million people drinking water contaminated by waste (Becker 2004). In India, which accounts for one-quarter of the world\u2019s child deaths owing to poor hygiene, only 200 of the country\u2019s 3,600 towns and cities are reported to have proper sewerage systems. Given these challenges, it is inconceivable how any of the Millennium Development Goals can be met without meeting MDG7, which includes targets to halve the proportion of people without access to potable water and to significantly improve the lives of at least 100 million slum dwellers by 2015.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata