nt}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2524567b-a3e5-469d-98b6-0ccb2aa96d04": {"__data__": {"id_": "2524567b-a3e5-469d-98b6-0ccb2aa96d04", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "52735e177c450595900d400a3f9f019e4f5b062950885f654c05cedb87407291"}}, "hash": "52735e177c450595900d400a3f9f019e4f5b062950885f654c05cedb87407291", "text": "of them in slums. Overcrowding increases risks for contracting communicable diseases. Ignoring of the environmental causes of health burden today will result in a massive \u201chealth debt\u201d that will be far more costly to pay off through curative measures in the future than to prevent the problems now, through basic water, sanitation, shelter and public health interventions. One analysis suggests that each US$1 invested in water and sanitation would yield an economic return of between US$3 and US$34 (Evans et al. 2004). The burden of illness and death from basic diarrhoeal diseases in Asia- Pacific is especially staggering. It is now evident that curing of sanitation problems through installation of facilities alone (e.g., constructing latrines) is inadequate. A complete community approach to sanitation, focusing on hygiene promotion, use of clean food, water and utensils, and hand washing with soap after defecation is more effective in reducing the transmission of diarrhoeal diseases, but these often result 15 from changes in community behaviour and cultural practices that are not spoken of frequently. There is a collective action problem in sanitation, where the actions of a single member affect all others in a community. This requires a collective response in the form of changing attitudes and investing in community infrastructure that follows from individual realisation of the \u201ccommunal\u201d nature of sanitation problems. This approach is, however, difficult to implement and could explain why sanitation has lagged behind demand for water (World Bank 2004, 174). Other forms of environmental support systems also can make significant contributions toward honouring human dignity and achievement of the MDGs. Take the unspoken issue of open defecation, a pervasive phenomenon in poor countries, where the dignity of hundreds of millions of women and men can be enhanced with the provision of clean, private sanitary facilities. Stakeholders responses to environmental problems In Asia-Pacific, enforceable environmental laws, regulations and institutions were mostly created by governments under pressure from NGOs and in response to the requirements of international funding agencies; public interest has been important, but not as powerful as in the industrialised countries, where policies responded to industrial technologies of the time as well as popular demand. While by the 1990s almost all Asian developing countries had formulated environmental standards, the record on compliance is poor in spite of provisions for sanctions to hold governments and commercial interests accountable for their performance. Inaction during the 1990s has been attributed to the view that \u201cthe environment can wait,\u201d which was subsequently overcompensated for by unrealistic regulatory regimes that never found traction (ADB 2000, 2). Environmental institutions in Asia have tested two new approaches: use of market-based instruments (MBIs) and increased disclosure of information on environmental violators. Most of the region\u2019s experience 16 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All has been with fiscal instruments. MBIs have not been used extensively, and so far, only a few have been tested (wastewater permit trading in China, permit trading for CFCs and traffic congestion in Singapore). This is a critical deficit, because market-creating instruments are particularly important in the regulation of privatised utilities. Most Pacific Island countries also have environmental regulations, with some using financial incentives for waste management and integrating freshwater resources with coastal management. There has been limited introduction of small advanced water treatment systems. As in Asia, the transference of plans into action in the Pacific Islands has been difficult (SPREP 2001, 24) The comparative responsiveness of the private sector may be assessed through the growth in the number of firms certified for ISO 9000 quality and ISO 14000 environmental management standards. China and the Republic of Korea have demonstrated remarkable growth in certification, with China now being the global leader, encompassing nearly 100,000 firms certified for quality management. In the leading countries, the dynamism of the private sector is a reason to be optimistic that society will be able to cope with looming issues such as climate change. The lagging countries are not isolated from the impacts of modernity, but have far more fragile coping capacities. The environmental industry and recent trends The environmental industry has grown to more than US$550 billion in revenues in 2003, accounting for 1.8 percent of the global economy (Ferrier et al. 2003, 10). The environmental services sector constitutes about half the total environment industry, valued in 2000 at about US$270 billion. The implicit distinction between environmental infrastructural services and environmental non-infrastructural services is important (Zarrilli 2003, 33). Human development priorities and civil society advocacy, as well as formal GATS classification of environmental services, are more concerned with the first cluster. 17 Broadly,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "eb913279-d3ff-4e38-8db7-adacc2cbbca9": {"__data__": {"id_": "eb913279-d3ff-4e38-8db7-adacc2cbbca9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "18a61d2d88b9a1967ba6273a8a1b8ff1da8bc02a89884443c5ee42df3143fb48"}}, "hash": "18a61d2d88b9a1967ba6273a8a1b8ff1da8bc02a89884443c5ee42df3143fb48", "text": "environmental services are defined as those activities that reduce environmental risk, minimise pollution and enable efficient resource use. The first set of such activities concerns pollution management (such as air pollution control, wastewater management, solid waste management, cleanup of soil and water, noise and vibration abatement, environmental monitoring, analysis, research, assessment and engineering). The second set of activities covers cleaner technology (aimed at eliminating or reducing the impact of technologies, processes and products). The third set falls under resource management, such as solid waste recycling and resource recovery. These environmental services have three important characteristics. First, they overlap with activities in just about all other sectors of the economy, from architecture and construction to auditing and risk assessment. Second, they have the properties of quasi-public goods,7 which make pricing based on consumer use difficult and have implications for human development concerns such as equity, universal provision and affordable access. Third, environmental services typically require large investment to ensure that collection and distribution networks reach the entire population. Owing to their quasi-public goods as well as natural monopoly properties, the public sector has been the primary provider of a range of environmental services until recently. None of the largest environmental companies in the world are from developing Asia-Pacific. The top 71 firms in the sector account for 20 percent of all revenues generated; most are American, but two of the largest are French.8 Other countries with leading firms are Germany, 7 Environmental services are not pure public goods, as classically defined with non-rivalry, non-excludability, and non-divisibility properties. Excludability in the provision of environmental services can be introduced (e.g. disconnecting water supply) and rivalry in consumption also exists (due to congestion in use). 8 There are changes in the fortunes of individual companies in recent years. The aggregate analysis for the distribution of firms remains valid. 18 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All Japan, and the United Kingdom. In terms of sectors within environmental services, solid waste management, water utilities and water treatment are the largest segments, the latter being the most capital-intensive. Firms in France and the U.K. have a lead in water and wastewater treatment, following past privatisation experiences of segments of their water utilities. In the past, U.S. firms were the most competitive in air pollution control services, largely because of the fact that the first comprehensive air quality legislation, the Clean Air Act, was passed in 1970 in the United States. Box 2: Thirsty Kathmandu: Private Participation in the Valley\u2019s Water Supply Even after four decades of donor assistance since the start of commercial water supply in 1966, there remains a huge gap in meeting the demand for potable water by the Kathmandu valley\u2019s 1.5 million people. The Government of Nepal formed a High-Level Private Sector Participation Committee (PSPC) in 1997 to hand over part of the water delivery system to a private operator by 1999. However, the requirement for the private operator to be internationally recognised and experienced in operating facilities similar in scale to the one in the Kathmandu valley resulted in only one company qualifying in each of the two unsuccessful privatisation attempts. In 2001 the World Bank ended its long involvement in the water supply management, and the Asian Development Bank (ADB) emerged as the new source of funds and advice. ADB helped develop the Kathmandu Valley Water Services Improvement Plan, which includes a proposal to divert water through a 26-kilometer tunnel from the snow-fed Melamchi River. One-third of the estimated US$464 million in costs will be financed with an ADB loan. Under this plan, a notice for \u201cexpression of interest\u201d was issued in January 2004 and necessary laws were enacted in April 2005. It is not clear yet if the Government can put in place the necessary institutions, including the Water Supply Management Board, Water Supply Tariff Fixation Commission and Water Utility Operator, in time to hand over operations to a private party by the target date of early 2006. The proposed water supply improvement plan has a provision for a Low- Income Consumer Support Unit (LICSU). Source: Dahal (2005) 19 Table 1: Select Environmental Indicators Country Population with Population with Children sustainable access to access to an underweight improved improved water (under age 5) sanitation (%) source (%) (%) 1990 2000 1990 2000 1995-2002a Bangladesh 41 48 94 97 48 Bhutan .. 70 .. 62 19 Cambodia .. 17 .. 30 45 China 29 c 40 71 75 11 Fiji .. 43 .. 47 8 b India 16 28 68 84 47 Indonesia 47 55 71 78 26", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3e654e59-3dcd-45d7-b0a2-9fa14ea8342b": {"__data__": {"id_": "3e654e59-3dcd-45d7-b0a2-9fa14ea8342b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b8f22b9afc59067fdfa1c3b1cc7ba2c5af882f531046f94848047b740d70864b"}, "3": {"node_id": "1d9d83de-0b7e-42ea-8ead-8b7c8c95b5db", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3828f1459f0ce230fc20d46bbd6459409e8