ng to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All economic costs of complying with environmental regulations (CIEL 2002, 7). Among the 44 top environmental market countries in the world, China ranked 12th in size and experienced the fastest growth, at a rate of 10.6 percent per annum. In particular, China has experienced unexpected growth in investment in the potable water and wastewater treatment segments. Several other Asian countries, like the Republic of Korea, Taiwan Province of China, and Viet Nam also have increased their investments in drinking water and wastewater treatment. The market in this segment is forecast to increase to US$62 billion by 2008 and US$117 billion by 2015 (Helmut Kaiser Consultancy 2004, 13). Other segments significant for Asian country imports are solid and hazardous waste, and recycling systems and remediation. The smallest volumes are in monitoring and analysis equipment, but this segment remains important for local capacity building. From a human development angle, the main policy concern over emerging attempts to open up trade in environmental services is the sweeping nature of multigenerational commitments that countries voluntarily lock themselves into, often without adequate national consultations. Even when projects are badly needed and make economic sense, a part of the general public's ex ante hostility to such schemes emanates from the desire to have these processes subjected to broad civic scrutiny before making long-term commitments. Water privatisation within and without trade agreements Comprising 90 percent of the brain, water is the most important molecule for survival of human life. Because it is simply a matter of life and death on the primary level, and because its secondary uses also are crucial for conduct of livelihoods, issues surrounding its access, quality and affordability deserve sensitive scrutiny and restraint in trade talks, especially those that conclude with binding commitments. Civil society organisations are rightly wary of proposals to liberalise systems that 23 collect, purify and distribute water, as expressed vocally during the Third World Water Forum in Kyoto, March 2003, and elsewhere. The Doha Ministerial Declaration, in paragraph 31 (iii), mandates negotiations on eliminating or reducing barriers to trade in environmental goods and services. The E.U. has since been actively pursuing the liberalisation of environmental services and also sectors that have bearing on water distribution and consumption, arguing that its proposal views the entire water cycle holistically, with both water distribution and wastewater treatment falling under \u201cresource use.\u201d GATS, as a WTO discipline, requires no privatisation or deregulation of public services like water distribution. Countries in fact have unambiguous policy options that they can retain by: i) Maintaining their service as a public or private monopoly, or ii) Opening the service to competing suppliers but restricting it to national companies, or iii) Opening the service to domestic and foreign suppliers and making no GATS commitments, or iv) Making GATS commitment covering the rights of foreign investors while attaching conditions (e.g., on technology transfer or freer movement of labourers) While all options exist and are available, and while no country so far has made any GATS commitment on water distribution, the fact that the issue of water has been brought to the negotiating table has been hugely controversial. Privatisation and liberalisation are separate processes, but in practice, privatisation is only theoretically distinct from liberalisation given the disparities between the capacities of national firms and multinationals in the sector. Privatisation of environmental services has been successful largely in the context of mature institutional and regulatory structures. Developing countries need to build up such capacities, first by incremental experiences with management service contracts, concessions and joint ventures. 24 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All Box 3: Water, Waste and FDI in China The first joint venture between Beijing and foreign companies in the sewage treatment sector, named the Beijing Municipal Drainage Co. Ltd., is the result of collaboration between the Government of China and the French Veolia Water Co. Ltd., Onyx waste services division, along with a Malaysia- based public utility company. The project, with a daily capacity of 100,000 tonnes and a total initial investment of 200 million yuan (about US$24 million) is expected to improve water quality of the Liangshui River, south of Beijing. The plant, located on the upper reaches of the river, is expected to benefit more than 350,000 local residents. The French giant also has recently won a US$737 million, 30-year contract to supply drinking water for the 2.5 million people in the city of Hohhot, in northern China\u2019s Inner Mongolia region. Separately, the company has sealed a US$233", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "41476097-813d-4309-a493-d2868afbf65b": {"__data__": {"id_": "41476097-813d-4309-a493-d2868afbf65b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development P