d's biggest potential market, the Ministry of Water Resources puts the cost of expected water- and sanitation-related infrastructure at US$26 billion by the end of 2005. Proponents of greater private sector involvement argue that recognition is growing that users do not pay the full cost of the water cycle, which begins in the skies, then goes to the reservoir and ends as wastewater. When the true value of the environmental resource is not accounted, there is wastage and resource degradation. This is one of the main reasons why water is not treated as a precious commodity and almost taken for granted (Wagl\u00e9 2004, 328). The prices determined by the private sector approximate toward charging the true costs of supplying a service and motivate prudent use of the resource. Further, there could be savings on grounds of efficiency. Governments also can put human development-friendly conditions on private suppliers by subjecting them to regulated prices and offering better billing and customer service to raise revenues, while upgrading the infrastructure for long-term sustainability. In other models, the full cost is shared between users and taxpayers as a \u201csustainable social price.\u201d There also could be ceiling rates on tariffs that cannot be exceeded, along with special provisions for low-income groups. Despite the uproar created by the possibility of private companies managing water sectors, only 5 percent of the world\u2019s water is actually distributed by the private sector.11 Even when private sectors take charge, they usually follow a process of \u201centrusting\u201d by the public 10 Gerard Mestrallet of Suez, quoted in The Economist, 19 July 2003. 11 The four big companies are Suez, Veolia, Saur and RWE. 26 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All authorities into a fixed-term contract. \u201cPrivatisation\u201d is often a misnomer \u2013 the management model could be a public-private partnership.12 The provisioning of water services through the public sector is thus a viable option, but approaches need to be innovative and yet ensure government oversight and transparency. Instances of public sector successes \u2013 e.g., Sao Paolo in Brazil, a city of 22 million, where a notable expansion of service has happened under public hands \u2013 provide adaptable lessons for Asia-Pacific. Whatever the model pursued, private companies have had to deal with fierce public opposition at times, sometimes leading to costly withdrawals. Because of high risks and difficulties in making profits in a highly regulated environment, the interest of international water companies in the poorest countries is diminishing. The viability of the market approach for providing these essential services in small markets and the poorest countries deserves a careful assessment (Zarrilli 2005, 3).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "18b5414b-6077-4b19-86dc-362f60948f84": {"__data__": {"id_": "18b5414b-6077-4b19-86dc-362f60948f84", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "77cda7b5715d274016e1e36f1fe680636e8fa8044151ea127f8a05ddeae12d78"