number of tankers. In league with groups in the Karachi Water and Sanitation Board (KWSB), they were alleged to have disconnected water supply to a number of areas, making them dependent on the tankers for their daily water requirements. When authorities investigated the KWSB and the water \u201cmafia,\u201d it discovered that the senior management was hostage to an extended kinship network controlling the middle management. The empty pipes had rusted and a restored water supply could not meet potable quality standards. The consumers thought they were better off with the tankers, which remain a booming business in the city (Qutub 2003, 44). The type of political regime also matters in the speed with which these schemes are pushed through. Take China and Viet Nam, one-party states with strong Governments: they have already experimented with water- related projects in major cities like Shanghai and Ho Chi Minh City. In China, Veolia signed a 50-year contract in 2002 worth nearly US$250 million to treat, distribute and collect fees for water in Shanghai. This subject is, however, considered too sensitive in countries with active elective politics like India and Thailand, where Governments have been forced to retract sensitive policy measures. GENCO in Thailand was 14 http://www.environmentprobe.org/ enviroprobe/pubs/ev542.htm 28 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All forced to reduce its treatment fees, while in Pakistan, the Government has had to reduce utility charges owing to public pressure. Box 4: Judicial Activism in Delhi\u2019s Air In 1998 Delhi was one of the world\u2019s 10 most polluted cities. The Indian Supreme Court, acting on a public interest litigation in 1996, passed a series of orders, the major one being introduction of Compressed Natural Gas (CNG) for public transport in 1998. Five years later, Delhi won the U.S. Department of Energy\u2019s Clean Cities International Partner of the Year award for \u2018\u2018bold efforts to curb air pollution and support alternative fuel initiatives.\u201d The city converted its entire public transport fleet to CNG. Compared to 1997, carbon monoxide is down by 32 percent and sulphur dioxide by 39 percent. The initiative is a testimony to judicial activism. Although the Government initially dilly-dallied to modify the Motor Vehicles Act to include CNG in its ambit, by November 2002 all public busses were converted to CNG. The lessons from Delhi to other cities in need of air quality changes are threefold: One, a comprehensive fuel strategy must be decided and agreed upon by all relevant actors; two, clear deadlines must be set for the implementation of policies; and three, a proactive administration is integral to the success of the project. Source: Adapted from Mumbai Newsline (26 May 2004) by K. Gupta. But like privatisation of other utilities, problems of corruption exist in water contracts, where the process often lacks transparency. Big multinational companies can siphon profits to other subsidiaries, and because contracts are very long-term, it is often hard to cancel them.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9b7b6107-8d91-42cd-b44f-d180bb6f9267": {"__data__": {"id_": "9b7b6107-8d91-42cd-b44f-d180bb6f9267", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/tra