 and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6a20260da9305716b09362fe52bc96643c129fb4b86e6476c2532fa21b79863c"}, "3": {"node_id": "016114cb-965e-4c5a-ba14-4cd74a6b55df", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "aa0d5daf88a27946d77a45b7546537c6bc5f49c7c22e5a28b1cc46ae0a051d46"}}, "hash": "ce4cd178e8b164df29e1cc04f3cc06222401d5902eb5daed97c603f98e48f8a6", "text": "has been working since 1980 to support people\u2019s efforts in upgrading Orangi township, a low-income informal settlement with more than 1 million residents in Karachi (a city whose Water and Sewerage Board does not reach the informal settlements that contain 60 percent of the city's population). The OPP model of sanitation comprises of internal development such as latrines, lane sewers and collector sewers at the neighbourhood levels. It has demonstrated that communities can finance and maintain internal development; contributing US$1.5 million, they have constructed hundreds of thousands of running feet of sewerage lines and sanitary pour-flush latrines in 90,000 houses. The OPP model has been replicated in 42 settlements in Karachi and in seven cities across Pakistan, with varying degrees of success. The critical factor is the degree to which local Government accepts the responsibility for external sanitation comprising trunk sewers and sewerage treatment (Hasan 1997, 11). In rural China, meanwhile, there exist models of cooperative non-profit water and sanitation delivery systems. In the early 1980s, only 50 percent of the rural population in China had access to safe water. By the end of 2002, this figure had reached 92 percent (868 million people). Among them, rural residents with access to piped water supply systems account for 57 percent of the total rural population, a 43 percent increase since 1985. Lessons to be learnt from this experience include: (a) importance of organisational and institutional capacity building; (b) community willingness to participate in financial contributions and sustainability; (c) necessity of sharing knowledge and understanding with users; and (d) integration of sanitation and health education with rural water supply.15 15 http://www.worldbank.org/wbi/reducingpoverty/case-China- RuralWaterandSanitation.html 30 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All There are other examples. Sulabh is an Indian NGO that has been active in sanitation and social reform for more than three decades, constructing and maintaining public toilets and twin-pit latrines for households. Sulabh has constructed more than 6,000 public latrines in 1,075 towns spread across India and converted more than 1.2 million bucket latrines into sanitary ones. It is estimated that more than 10 million people use Sulabh\u2019s facilities every day (Sulabh 2004, 25). Arguably, many civil society organisations in Asia-Pacific have locked themselves into a service delivery mode that supplants rather than supplements grassroots and local Government capacities. The more difficult \u2013 but more rewarding \u2013 work of creating the demand for environmental services is being neglected. At the same time, the recognition of the importance of civic engagement and participation in debates on reforming utilities is growing. Thailand's new constitution, in its Articles 45 and 46, requires stakeholder consultations before project undertakings that might affect livelihoods or the environment. In addition to building up and replicating low-cost, pro-poor indigenous models, Asia-Pacific countries need to ensure that liberalisation is preceded by enhanced domestic legislative and regulatory infrastructures that sustain these approaches. The daunting new demands for services and overwhelming fiscal shortage means that countries will inevitably need to draw on foreign technology and capital. The relevant question to ask, thus, is not whether to open up to foreign investment, but what segment, when, how fast, and with what kind of policy safeguards in place. Liberalisation of environmental services: Marrying investment needs with social obligations The overarching need is to match the legitimate investment crunch in environmental services with human development obligations. Can this be best handled within GATS or unilaterally? If countries decide to undertake commitments on environmental services, or sub-sectors within, at the WTO, what should they see as their framework of 31 potential benefits and losses, and how should they go about framing their responses? Commitments to liberalise in environmental services could be traded off for meaningful reciprocal offers to enhance domestic capacity, or improve access for labour movement, or promote agriculture and fisheries exports. Liberalisation on the part of developing countries also could be tied to conditions such as transfer of technology, which could in turn contribute to implementing Articles IV and XIX of GATS that aim at increasing the participation of developing countries in world trade in services. There also exists a longstanding argument to treat the two factors of production (labour and capital) symmetrically, and to balance Mode 3 and Mode 4 commitments. Developing countries should pursue this point with persistence.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__