"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0ccd0004-9ba4-4fd9-a5fb-70525ff372e7": {"__data__": {"id_": "0ccd0004-9ba4-4fd9-a5fb-70525ff372e7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bebba2550b9ae092e1ee548535e681f54bdc05b5e8ae75ef80644871d6c59f50"}, "3": {"node_id": "78112a18-b70b-415f-8d1c-512b356358de", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c9449344e0c039af6b6f8b6a82bda0989db7b23ade3a33f8d3ed9ce5a4e4f8bf"}}, "hash": "e12dd1eb02b6f05698d9073083a3213eb9a3b62f1205e2f7676a4086c19f0e63", "text": "service sectors, the supply of basic environmental services involves large investments that could become profitable only over long periods of time, thus making effective control a major factor in investment. At the WTO, there is no agreed template on what environmental services constitute. The current definition includes: sewerage services, refuse disposal services, sanitation and similar services, cleaning of exhaust gases, noise abatement services, and nature and landscape protection services; the latter draws on a 1991 document called the W120 and refers to the United Nations Central Product Classification. This definition has been criticised for being too narrow and not reflecting market realities. In sending requests to WTO members, the European Commission proposed its own classification (based on the 32 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All OECD-Eurostat definition16 of \u201cenvironmental,\u201d which includes, among others, water for human use.17 The formal state of play in the request/offer process cannot easily be determined since information is seldom released publicly, but leaked documents relating to the EC\u2019s first batch of requests, in 2003 to 109 countries, caused a lot of interest. The United States in its initial offer on GATS, while accepting the broader classification of environmental services, has excluded \u201cwater for human use\u201d in the sector-specific commitments. Among the Asian WTO members, six made commitments on environmental services, namely, Cambodia, China, Japan, Nepal, Republic of Korea and Thailand. Four countries have made full market access commitments on all sub-sectors. Republic of Korea limited individual foreign investor ownership of individual companies to 6 percent. In Thailand, foreign equity participation must not exceed 49 percent of the registered capital, and the number of foreign shareholders must be less than half the total number of shareholders of the company. In acceding to the WTO, Nepal undertook commitments strategically. It liberalised 11 services sectors and 70 sub-sectors, which on the surface is high for an LDC. However, a thorough study of the limitations entered in horizontal commitments as well as market access and national treatment columns tells a different story. Its objective was to liberalise only those services sectors in which: a) the Nepali private sector may never get involved, given the huge sunk cost and high gestation period 16 The Eurostat definition of the environmental industry consists of \u201cactivities which produce goods and services to measure, prevent, limit, minimise or correct environmental damage to water, air, and soil, as well as problems related to waste, noise and ecosystems. This includes cleaner technologies, products and services which reduce environmental risk and minimise pollution and resource use.\u201d The EC is approaching the entire water cycle holistically and argues that this is covered under \u201cresource use.\u201d 17 Only 0.1 percent of the world\u2019s water is for human use; more than 99 percent is saline, or glacier or snow (UNEP Atlas 2005). 33 (e.g., pipeline transportation); b) the Nepali private sector is already competitive and is confident that it would be able to outperform the foreign service suppliers, even if the sector concerned is liberalised (e.g., banking services); and c) the sectors where employment potential for the locals is high, e.g., computer and related services (Adhikari 2005). While regional banks and IFIs have often made the case for privatisation of utilities, shifts have occurred in recent years. The World Bank now sees the privatisation of water as \u201cproblematic,\u201d calling for the building up of regulatory capacity, especially for clarity of roles among various levels of government and the regulatory agency. Concessions and leases are more effective than privatisation to achieve efficiencies of competition while retaining strong public oversight (Kessides 2004, 15). Even so, concerns would remain on the grounds of equity and sustainability. The profit-seeking behaviour of private firms, especially under conditions of monopoly, is likely to result in price hikes and exclusion of the poor unable to pay increased rates. Environmental sustainability is a concern as well; for example, a private firm may indulge in unsustainable withdrawal of underground water. In fact, all forms of negative externalities need to be rigorously addressed. Efficient waste collection by a private company may be accompanied by more dumping of trash on sensitive wetlands, as has happened in Chennai, India (Sawhney and Chanda 2003, 23). Overall, there is secrecy in GATS negotiations and an overwhelming lack of understanding of WTO provisions among Government officials.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "78112a18-b70b-415f-8d1c-512b356358de": {"__data__": {"id_": "78112a18-b70b-415f-8d1c-512b356358de", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bebba2550b9ae092e1ee548535e681f54bdc05b5e8ae75ef80644871d6c59f50"}, "2": {"node_id": "0ccd0004-9ba4-4fd9-a5fb-70525ff372e7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e12dd1eb02b6f05698d9073083a3213eb9a3b62f1205e2f7676a4086c19f0e63"}}, "hash": "c9449344e0c039af6b6f8b6a82bda0989db7b23ade3a33f8d3ed9ce5a4e4f8bf", "text": "Discussions on the assessment of proposals are not transparent, limited as they are to a narrow group of specialised civil servants. Because most stakeholders are not engaged in these discussions in many countries most of the time, negotiators may not be sensitised enough to the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7bd165a4-1c8a-4844-a755-8343fc8772e5": {"__data__": {"id_": "7bd165a4-1c8a-4844-a755-8343fc8772e5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c99a8e61a431f09f392233cf9ae487e73208fd0c0047916a25753ddb22f34338"}}, "hash": "c99a8e61a431f09f392233cf9ae487e73208fd0c0047916a25753ddb22f34338", "text": "importance of environmental services that are needed and potentially available for improving people\u2019s health. 34 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All Box 5: Types of Private Participation Management service contracts: The Government remains the primary provider of the service and private operators are hired to carry out designated tasks. This is a low-risk option of service contracts, most appropriate when only operational efficiency is required without significant new investment. Build operate transfer (BOT) and build operate own (BOO): Under BOT, private investment is invited to construct and operate new facilities for an extended period so as to allow recovery of cost and earning of profit. Government retains ownership of the infrastructure facility. A BOO (or BOOT) is a long-term concession contract where the infrastructure assets entrusted to the private party remain Government property, and the Government remains the regulator. Joint ventures: Private and public sectors together assume co- ownership of assets and co-responsibility for the delivery of services, by forming a new company or sharing ownership of an existing company. Full Privatisation: The Government grants the responsibility of providing the service and ownership to the private party. The Government only functions as the regulator of quality and prices. Source: Qutub (2003) Moving forward The human development paradigm views people as the end of all state efforts. The following indicators for empowerment, productivity, equity and sustainability appear most relevant to the environmental services industry: Empowerment: Employment Generation; Transparency and Accountability 35 Productivity: Economic Efficiency; Technology Transfer Equity: Basic Access; Fair Access Sustainability: Technological Sustainability; Environmental Quality The advantage of working with these indicators is that they are objectively verifiable. This list can be useful when countries find themselves confronted with requests to liberalise trade in environmental services, and they ask themselves two pertinent questions: i) Which sub- sectors offer the best opportunities for enhancing human development through liberalisation? ii) At the other extreme, where are the risks for human development? In considering these questions, policymakers should take note of the following sets of issues: First, services provided directly to industry offer a win-win opportunity for stakeholders and society at large. In particular, effluent treatment plants can achieve economies of scale in an industrial estate setting. Because the clients are industrial establishments, there is no risk of marginalising any poor stakeholder. Society benefits because negative externalities are assigned to point sources of pollution and regulation ensures that the polluter is charged appropriately. A level playing field encourages compliance among users. Management contracts or concessions for industrial wastewater treatment reduce administrative costs and support efficiency. Worldwide experience confirms that feasible levels of pollution charges can meet the capital and operating costs of the services provided. Any surplus revenues can be assigned to improving the quality of the general public welfare. A liberalised private sector regime for Combined Effluent Treatment Plants could thus bring more FDI, break local institutional gridlocks and provide respectability to Asia-Pacific processors in world markets. The clientele would be industry, and there is no risk of excluding the poor. Second, employment displacement in the solid waste management sub- sector is one of the greatest risks associated with trade liberalisation. Excessive mechanisation targets the livelihoods of some of the poorest 36 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All people. The exclusion of low-income communities from privatised and liberalised water supply and solid waste management services are also serious risks. In addition, there is considerable risk that biodiversity conservation projects managed by international consortiums will fence off parks and protected areas and deprive the poor of their traditional access rights. Third, one longer-term strategic opportunity for developing countries is to export labour and skill intensive environmental services. Other opportunities include securing recognition for watershed management in upland areas and traditional biodiversity management as environmental services, traded across borders or consumed abroad. Fourth, on the specific subject of water for human consumption within environmental services, there is a strong human rights dimension that must be recognized as on par with similar rights to basic food and adequate housing. This has been discussed in the United Nations High Commission for Human Rights, where countries have been urged to assess how trade policies affect human rights. The key point is that states have, over the years, undertaken many international human rights treaty obligations which need to be respected by WTO members during their negotiations and while implementing commitments to liberalise trade in managing air, water and waste. Fifth, multilateral negotiations are conducted on the basis of reciprocity that countries should", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "afa8bd85-0326-4b67-8aa9-70db6ce59117": {"__data__": {"id_": "afa8bd85-0326-4b67-8aa9-70db6ce59117", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8ab67a320f22df24d9627a69df108b0a80d8b5fedd3fef29afcda50cfd492655"}}, "hash": "8ab67a320f22df24d9627a69df108b0a80d8b5fedd3fef29afcda50cfd492655", "text": "optimize by seeking concessions in areas of export interest to them, in return for considered access to environmental market. While there is no evidence that GATS commitments automatically lead to increase in FDI, they could send a signal of sorts to investors. GATS also could lock in not only economic policy, but also human development-friendly measures that countries could not retract owing to vested pressures at a later date. The flip side, however, is that reneging on commitments can lead to costly trade sanctions. 37 Sixth, with coalition building around such experiential learning, developing countries of Asia-Pacific could embed reform and investment needs in their national anti-poverty strategies that comprehensively address water, sanitation and public health challenges through multiple channels: direct public investments, stage-wise privatisation, scaling up of participatory community-led approaches, and engagement in international trade. A comprehensive strategy that leverages all policy possibilities is the only way countries have any chance in filling parts of the glaring gaps in access, use and affordability of mainly water and sanitation. This bottom-up approach of home-grown policies also will assist countries to respond strategically to requests during sectoral trade negotiations at the bilateral, regional and global levels. 38 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All III. International trade in energy services and human development The scale of development challenges It will be nearly impossible to achieve any of the MDGs without the availability of adequate, affordable and clean energy, given its pervasive role in human life. More than 1.5 billion people in the world have no access to electricity; most live in rural Asia and sub-Saharan Africa. The average electrification rate in South Asia is only 41 percent, less than half the average for Southeast Asia and China (87 percent). Nearly 2.5 billion people rely on traditional biomass for cooking and heating, of which 72 percent live in Asia. The data show that the higher the level of biomass consumption, the higher the extent of poverty. They suggest an inverse correlation between the extent of biomass energy consumption and key demographic indicators such as life expectancy and infant mortality. The absence of modern energy undermines efforts to raise the living standards of the poor, especially in rural areas, and prevents them from enhancing their livelihood opportunities. Energy can play a catalytic role in development, but this takes place in conjunction with other complementary development inputs, such as water supply, health facilities, market access and credit. This has been recognised by the United Nations under its WEHAB (Water and Sanitation, Energy, Health, Agriculture and Biodiversity) Framework presented at the World Summit for Sustainable Development 2002, which highlights the interconnections between energy and other factors that contribute to human development. In developing countries, important barriers in the way of supplying modern energy services (fuels and electricity) to the poor consist of the following: First, in rural areas, the primary problem is the poor\u2019s inability to access modern energy because supplies simply do not reach them. Transporting electricity and fossil fuels requires capital-intensive distribution networks for which remoteness and low levels of demand are major 39 constraints. The farther the poor are from the reach of such networks, the greater the difficulties of operating supply utilities on financial sustainability principles. Second, the poor lack purchasing power. As a result, even where communities as a whole have access, the poor among them have to forego the benefits of modern energy. The transition from traditional biomass energy and human/animal labour to efficient modern resources and appliances invariably \u201ccommercialises\u201d energy, since all modern energy options carry a price. Low incomes set a low threshold of affordability among the poor, with the want of energy competing with other survival needs. Third, insufficient cost-effectiveness is a crucial barrier to enhance affordability. Cost-effectiveness can be ensured when there is a multiplicity of energy services, and service providers to select from. The poor in developing countries have limited choices in both, partly due to resource and technology limitations but equally because of policies restricting the emergence of diverse and competitive energy markets. Fourth, rural poverty affects men and women differently, with women bearing a disproportionate share of hardship. Women are responsible for onerous and time-consuming tasks in collecting and using traditional fuels on rudimentary stoves. This has direct consequences for women, ranging from serious health impacts caused by indoor pollution to lost opportunities for self-improvement. Energy security and trade An overarching concern in the energy sector is energy security: the growth and preservation of international supply lines for critical fossil fuels and, in some cases, electricity. With growing economic", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "678d5a6c-d060-476b-854d-2ba41847bb4b": {"__data__": {"id_": "678d5a6c-d060-476b-854d-2ba41847bb4b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publicat