hbouring countries under bilateral agreements. The outreach of this trade is now expanding beyond immediate borders and across continents. China has a 50 percent 44 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All share in Iran\u2019s Yadavaran oil field; China National Petroleum Corporation owns 60 percent of Kazakhstan's Aktobemunigaz; Sinopec has invested US$1 billion in a joint venture with Brazil\u2019s Petrobas for a gas pipeline; and in the latest bold move, China National Offshore Oil Corporation made a US$18.5 billion bid for Unocal, a U.S. oil and gas company. Similarly, India\u2019s Oil and Natural Gas Corporation has invested in offshore gas fields in Viet Nam and in energy projects in Algeria, Kazakhstan, Indonesia, Venezuela, Libya and Syria; an Indian private group, Reliance Industries, has a stake in an offshore field in Yemen, and ONGC Videsh Ltd. has acquired a 20 percent share in Russia's Far Eastern Sakhalin-1 field.19 \ufffd On an intra-regional basis, new initiatives have been launched to foster trade in gas and electricity. Notable among these are the ASEAN Gas Grid, ASEAN Power Pool, Greater Mekong Sub-Region Power Grid, SAARC Regional Grid and the Iran-Pakistan-India gas pipeline20 projects. These are being accompanied by efforts to scale up the volume of existing bilateral energy trade arrangements such as, for example, electricity trade between Nepal and India. \ufffd Gradual deregulation of the publicly owned energy industry in as many as 16 countries of the region \u2013 China, India, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Nepal, Pakistan, Philippines, Singapore, Sri Lanka, Thailand, Viet Nam \u2013 has triggered fundamental market transformations leading to new opportunities for trade in energy goods and services (WEC 1998). The majority of independent power producers (IPPs) in several of these countries is foreign-owned, and new policy emphasis on renewable energy also has led to the entry of foreign technology suppliers. 19 http://in.rediff.com/money/2005/jul/05guest1.htm 20 India and Iran signed a deal worth US$ 22 billion on 13 June 2005. Iran would supply 5 million tons of liquefied natural bas annually over a 25-year period beginning in 2009. 45 Box 7: Thailand\u2019s Small Power Producers Programme Thailand\u2019s new \u201cNet Metering\u201d system will allow sustainable energy producers to literally \u201cspin the meter backwards\u201d in the production of new clean energies. With electricity consumption growing at 6 percent annually, and the task of building power plants increasingly challenging, this new Thai legislation that allows small-scale renewable energy producers (up to 1 MW per installation) to feed energy that they do not use back into the power grid represents an inventive solution to a persistent problem. Compensation is earned in terms of the \u201cbulk supply tariff\u201d which, at the average cost of power generation and transmission, is around 80 percent of the retail rate.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2802e7e8-f078-4411-88b1-08c1c10a599b": {"__data__": {"id_": "2802e7e8-f078-4411-88b1-08c1c10a599b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher":