Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b6f050ff041ea2350abaf8784316ae6f878b6df915dd397f7d4172a1df64a51c"}}, "hash": "b6f050ff041ea2350abaf8784316ae6f878b6df915dd397f7d4172a1df64a51c", "text": "existing global energy supply lines from established importers like Japan and the Western countries. With energy demand expanding at comparable rates in other countries, investment in the region\u2019s energy infrastructure will average around 3.5 percent of GDP (more than 8 percent of GDP in some countries like Papua New Guinea), presenting 21 China is the second-largest importer of oil, presently requiring 2 million barrels of foreign oil per day; this is expected to rise fivefold by 2025 (BBC World News 26 June). 46 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All the most compelling reason to seek market transformations capable of attracting private capital.22 Global estimates of energy investment needs vary, with the International Energy Agency placing it at US$16 trillion worldwide for 2001-2030 (IEA 2003), and the World Energy Council (WEC) nearly doubling this at US$30 trillion. A breakdown of the former indicates that power generation, transmission and distribution will absorb almost 60 percent of the aggregate cost. Investments in the oil and gas sectors will each amount to more than US$3 trillion, or around 19 percent of global energy investment. The coal industry will require US$400 billion, or 2 percent. The five largest countries outside the OECD \u2013 Brazil, China, India, Indonesia and Russia \u2013 will need about one-third of global electricity investment. Financing these investments will be one of the biggest challenges of the generation. With the coming into force of the Kyoto Protocol to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) in February 2005, environmental considerations are becoming a major driver of new energy technology. Advanced technologies being developed today could dramatically alter energy choices and requirements in the longer term. The transfer of these technologies to developing countries will add a new dimension to established patterns of trade in energy. However, even assuming a generous scale of technology transfer from the rich to developing countries, the energy needs of the latter will continue to grow, in part because of their very low levels of energy consumption per capita at present and in part due to continued population growth.23 Short of dramatic breakthroughs in energy efficiency, the gains from the induction of improved present-day technologies into developing 22 APEC (2003) 23 Much of the world population growth up to and beyond 2050 will occur in developing countries. 47 countries will at least be partially offset by absolute growth in their energy demands and higher rates of per capita energy consumption. Against this background, market opening measures have gathered momentum in Asia-Pacific, with a growing number of countries finding it necessary to introduce structural reforms to cut costs and improve economic performance. These measures include: a) Deregulation (reducing state control) b) Corporatisation (placing public energy utilities under commercial discipline) c) Unbundling (breaking up vertically integrated, state-owned monopolies into smaller units, with portions of the energy supply industry passed on to the private sector) d) Private sector participation (joint ventures, energy service companies) and e) Privatisation (independent energy producers). The overall thrust of these reforms is to introduce competition in order to reduce expenditure on energy production, reorient decision-making to incorporate private rather than public economics, and establish more transparent pricing to better reflect energy costs. The underlying reasoning is that without massive investments, including foreign investment, it is not possible to meet the growing energy needs of developing countries through public investment and ODA alone. The central aim of the reforms is to enlarge access to cheaper, more efficient energy which, in turn, will enhance the productivity of people and enable them to compete in a globalised world. Significant energy sector reforms are now taking place in at least 13 countries of the region (WEC 1998). While progress is being made, none of the developing countries involved has achieved a substantial level of liberalisation comparable to the industrialised countries. Reforms across the board covering electricity, coal, oil and gas are occurring only in India. In other countries, one or more of these industries are undergoing structural 48 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All changes, with the majority of countries concentrating on reforms in electricity. The general direction of reforms is toward a diminishing influence of government, especially in terms of price controls and guaranteed markets. This involves a transfer in ownership either from central government to government-owned independent enterprises, or from government-owned to private companies; removal of import quotas and duties, and a reduction in government subsidies. Progress with the reforms has been mixed thus far. In the majority of countries,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6cd211a6-898f-4e6f-a3d3-24b9e209963f": {"__data__": {"id_": "6cd211a6-898f-4e6f-a3d3-24b9e209963f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e78fd4b29f9fb12cceb7608e400df2adc09552127ecf30e5be781b00aa6b0e1b"}}, "hash": "e78fd4b29f9fb12cceb7608e400df2adc09552127ecf30e5be781b00aa6b0e1b", "text": "control of the industry remains with the central or local/state governments. Privately owned domestically-controlled, and privately owned domestically-and-internationally controlled power utilities are present only in the advanced economies of Hong Kong SAR, Japan and the Republic of Korea. However, private entities coexist with public utilities in Sri Lanka, where the latter retains its predominance, and in the Philippines, where private ownership is more influential. The Power Sector Reform Act and the Downstream Oil Industry Deregulation Act in the Philippines have sought to attract private sector investments while ensuring fair and reasonable energy prices. The former mandates the reduction of electricity prices and addresses the issue of access by stipulating that distribution utilities are required to provide universal service within their franchise areas (Pacudan 2003). In the majority of countries, the electricity industry remains vertically integrated with generation, transmission and distribution vested in government entities and pricing mostly regulated by the government. Independent regulators or competitive markets have yet to become prevalent. Although, as noted, these reforms have revolved around domestic markets, they have facilitated foreign capital, technology and energy flows. 49 Liberalising trade in energy services So far, the ongoing energy reforms in developing countries have concentrated largely on domestic markets. There are now calls to extend them further into the international arena. Energy resources are not the focus of these moves because states need to retain control of these resources for the welfare of present and future generations. The calls have more to do with the numerous activities, or \u201cservices,\u201d that go into the extraction, production, transformation, transportation and delivery of each \u201cenergy chain.\u201d The energy market is highly segmented, with more than 30 different types of such services that can be singled out as \u201cadding value\u201d to each stage linking an energy source to the final consumer (Zarrilli 2003, 25). The considerations for liberalising upstream services are different from transportation and downstream services. The Doha Development Agenda is the first time that energy policy measures have come under multilateral trade negotiations. The proposals on energy services are aimed at gaining greater access to markets being liberalised by reducing the potential of residual monopolies to frustrate competition. Initial \u201coffers\u201d at the WTO in the energy sector are difficult to assess because of scattered commitments,24 but qualitatively not much is on the table (South Centre 2005). Classification-related issues have attracted much attention in GATS proposals because they reflect the liberalisation goals of the United States, Japan, Chile and the European Union. These countries are pressing for liberalisation of upstream energy services with the aim of increasing and securing control of supplies. Some proposals also reflect domestic strategies for liberalisation of segments within the energy chain, such as in Indonesia. While it is generally acknowledged that the energy sector will continue to be regulated to pursue public goals, the outcome of negotiations on 24 From developed countries, the United States, Norway, Australia and the European Commission have made initial offers, and from developing countries, Egypt, Colombia, Chile and India, among others. 50 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All other key issues on the Doha Agenda could have potential implications for energy policies and human development, including subsidies and countervailing measures. These issues have been raised in negotiations of accession to the WTO, along with \u201cWTO-plus\u201d requests in the areas of governmental controls on production and export of petroleum-based products; domestic prices and pricing policy; export tariffs and taxation; the operations of state trading enterprises; and \u201cunfair\u201d trade practices (Gibbs 2003). Box 8: Indonesia\u2019s Strategic Approach GATS negotiating positions reflect domestic strategies such as those of Indonesia, which is liberalising the downstream segment of the energy sector to improve its refineries, mainly to be able to refine its own oil. Indonesia hopes to attract foreign investors who would bring the capital and technology needed to improve domestic refinery capacity. Indonesia also is liberalising the upstream segment of the energy sector and has recently privatised the national oil company, Pertamina. However, it wishes to attract only domestic private investors for now, because it believes that domestic companies would not be able to compete with foreign companies right away. In November 2004, Indonesia introduced at the WTO a revised proposal for classification of energy services with the aim of achieving a high level of desegregation in energy service activities. This would allow countries, especially energy-endowed developing countries, to liberalise only the specific sub-segments that they wish to liberalise. Source: Zarrilli (2005) The GATS proposals are consistent with the relative investment priorities outlined in the IEA scenario referred to earlier. They", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "47d8c689-906b-4ae5-b088-3a99643b5fb2": {"__data__": {"id_": "47d8c689-906b-4ae5-b088-3a99643b5fb2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "be1b4589583a8d5eb95d7f51c3a81ecc7fdaaa88e544991fca6aa93fc8ed3289"}}, "hash": "be1b4589583a8d5eb95d7f51c3a81ecc7fdaaa88e544991fca6aa93fc8ed3289", "text": "revolve around the markets for electricity, oil, gas and coal. In sheer investment terms, the electricity sector is most important, followed by the oil and gas sector where, aside from the volume of estimated investment, 51 concerns over supply security are added motivations. As a result, considerable attention is paid to gas transportation and transmission via tankers and pipelines. While coal features in broad-based requests for energy sector-wide access, its relative importance is low. In the case of oil, gas and coal, there is a stress on upstream services that are more capital-intensive than downstream services. Electricity transmission and distribution are, however, of considerable interest since the projected investment in them is larger than that in generation and exceeds the combined total of the oil and gas sectors. Of the four \u201cmodes\u201d of supply, Mode 1 is relevant for online trading and energy brokering and professional services that can be delivered by mail or electronically, such as consulting or legal services. It also covers services related to the cross-border transmission of electricity and gas through pipelines and interconnected grids. Mode 3 is the most important because it covers all different forms of foreign commercial presence, such as BOT25 contractors and IPPs. Mode 4 includes the movement of skilled personnel who deliver technical and managerial services, as well as the movement of semi-skilled and unskilled personnel needed, for example, for the construction and upgrading of grids. Potential human development impacts of energy market liberalisation Access to cheaper, more efficient energy through market reforms and trade liberalisation can mitigate the energy security concerns of developing countries, help sustain their economic growth prospects, and enhance the productivity of their people. These developments can enable developing countries to compete in a globalised world. However, reforms and liberalisation imply that governments will no longer be able to apply direct measures in the energy sector in support of human development goals, but shall have to pursue them through new regulatory structures. 25 Build, operate and transfer. 52 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All Asian experiences to date with energy market reforms represent a transition whose pace and eventual destination are still uncertain, given that the starting point for each country is different and that there are concerns over the human development impacts of open markets for energy. Taking the example of the electricity sector, where the most progressive reforms are occurring, developing countries have to cross several stages \u2013 from initial corporatisation of state utilities to full retail competition \u2013 before achieving the kind of substantially liberalised energy markets that are being advocated by development banks and their shareholding industrialised countries. Recent setbacks with liberalised energy markets in the United States have, however, prompted Asian countries to adopt a more cautious approach.26 Although these developments should not deter countries from the long-term benefits of energy liberalisation, they are nonetheless a warning against the potentially serious public interest consequences of hasty marketisation. Available evidence suggests that the price reduction benefits of liberalisation are long-term rather than short-term. By contrast, the current emphasis of energy strategies on human development seems to require a higher rather than lower level of regulatory intervention by the state. This points to the need for a graduated approach to liberalisation, accompanied by adequate regulatory safeguards in line with equity gaps in individual countries. As nations grapple with domestic reforms and international requests to trade in energy services, their potential impact on important human development variables must be noted. A recent review carried out by the 26 In 2001, Enron, the world\u2019s largest private energy company \u2013 with 21,000 employees, 25,000 miles of gas pipelines and 9,000 MW of electricity generating capacity in the United States and abroad \u2013 collapsed, with subsequent enquiries revealing widespread price-rigging practices. In a related development, the privatised electricity market in California underwent a series of convulsions, leaving hundreds of thousands of consumers without electricity and major power corporations in bankruptcy, requiring repeated Governmental interventions to ensure power supply 53 UNDP Asia-Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative in five countries of the region sheds light on the nature of these impacts.27 \ufffd Energy consumption: In absolute terms, evidence suggests that market and trade liberalisation will lead to an increase in the growth of modern energy consumption at the overall national level. It is unlikely this will take place evenly across all segments of the population, however. Countries with large rural populations without access to modern energy cannot expect profit-seeking private firms to enter rural energy markets readily. Nonetheless, decentralised renewable energy programmes with private initiative can", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "87d2a156-662b-40c6-8b72-887e1a2fd4bc": {"__data__": {"id_": "87d2a156-662b-40c6-8b72-887e1a2fd4bc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3cda0e97f1177e8e404aac0c575f9b5b2ff3fb2603f845ad39776580618435a4"}}, "hash": "3cda0e97f1177e8e404aac0c575f9b5b2ff3fb2603f845ad39776580618435a4", "text": "increase modern energy consumption in rural areas. \ufffd Energy prices and affordability: Energy price increases are likely to occur in almost all cases of liberalisation. Competitive electricity markets do not support price subsidies and cross-subsidies. Price increases could be offset over time by efficient production, construction and transportation/transmission technologies, coupled with subsidies and lifeline rates targeted at the poor. The initial costs of decentralised renewable energy technologies could decrease gradually as market expansion takes place and economies of scale kick in. However, in the short to medium term, the price impacts are likely to be largely negative. \ufffd Universal access: Ensuring universal access to electricity and modern fuels implies the supply of a minimum quantity of modern energy to meet the basic needs of all. Market or trade liberalisation can, at best, contribute to the overall state effort aimed at universal access by easing supply constraints. 27 Refer to country case studies (on China, India, Iran, Malaysia and the Philippines) prepared by the UNDP Asia-Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative. 54 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All \ufffd Employment and income: The potential for income growth due to liberalisation is mixed. For instance, in China coal industry reforms left 1.5 million workers unemployed. On the other hand, expansion of the energy industry as a whole due to market-opening could add new functions and employment opportunities. New jobs may occur in other economic sectors as higher energy consumption leads to economic expansion. \ufffd Rural-urban income disparity and migration: Even if liberalisation leads to greater energy availability for rural populations, no assurance exists that this will result in rural economic development that can arrest migration and reduce income disparities, given that energy is one of several inputs to rural development. \ufffd Human resource development and capacity building: In all five countries assessed by UNDP, liberalisation has transferred technical and managerial skills and knowledge from the developed countries along the energy chain, especially in exploration, production and transmission/transportation facilities. Further liberalisation can enhance these benefits, more so if it leads to enhanced local manufacturing capacity in energy equipment. \ufffd Education/literacy: Impacts on education and literacy will be negligible. The problem lies with low levels of modern energy supply to rural households. The level of illumination provided by lighting fuels and decentralised electricity is usually inadequate except for basic visibility. This is partly due to supply constraints, but more because of low incomes and the need for households to minimise their energy expenditures. \ufffd Health and local environmental protection: Liberalisation is expected to usher in new, environmentally cleaner technologies in various activities along the energy chain. Traditional biomass cooking fuels in rural households, which are a major cause of local environmental 55 degradation and poor indoor air quality, are likely to be replaced by less-polluting fuels like kerosene and LPG. However, fossil fuel consumption is likely to increase with liberalisation, with potential adverse effects on health and environment. \ufffd Gender equity: The gender dimension of energy has to do largely with the time spent by rural women in the time-consuming tasks of traditional fuel collection, preparation and cooking. Time savings for women in these activities cannot be realised from the promotion of kerosene and electricity, because these are intended for non-cooking uses. As a result, their enhanced supply, made possible through private networks and providers under a more open market climate, might carry other impacts but have little effect on women unless household incomes increase sufficiently to make cooking fuels like LPG affordable. \ufffd Small and medium enterprise development: Liberalisation will generally benefit SME development. However, countries with a large unemployed work force could be adversely affected in construction activities where local SMEs could be displaced by multinational presence. Negative impacts also are anticipated in wholesale and retail energy trade activities where foreign firms could replace the traditional role of distribution utilities and local contracting firms. \ufffd Energy security and strategic supply control: The ability of governments to retain strategic control over energy production and distribution is generally expected to diminish in a competitive market environment. To the extent that the operation and management of such services pass from the hands of state-owned utilities to free market players, there are potential adverse effects for national strategic interest and for lifeline supplies to marginalised populations. \ufffd Policy response flexibility: The ability of governments to exercise policy responses is expected to diminish under a more competitive 56 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All environment where regulation, taxes and other forms of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8d893771-ec31-4f36-8a00-fab7c0c625db": {"__data__": {"id_": "8d893771-ec31-4f36-8a00-fab7c0c625db", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "45d2725da0d6dd2f28a1636e6f5bf640f5013f5a2170e2af9e4eeb0d9c75fa19"}}, "hash": "45d2725da0d6dd2f28a1636e6f5bf640f5013f5a2170e2af9e4eeb0d9c75fa19", "text": "government intervention in the market give way to more direct interaction between buyers and sellers. Although governments will continue to make broader policy decisions to pursue national strategic interests and welfare goals, these are not likely to allow them the kind of policy response capability that they have through state-owned utilities. \ufffd Efficient resource use: Resource use is expected to receive a boost, since this is a key strength of the market. Subject to continuing regulatory policies that ensure the community and welfare obligations of the government and also of the private sector, liberalisation will better reflect the scarcity value of primary energy sources in prices; introduce more efficient technologies; allow redundancies in overstaffed state-owned utilities; and bring in more effective financial planning and management tools. Box 9: Health Effects of Biomass Use on Women Biomass cooking on traditional stoves is a major source of concentrated air pollutants, including carbon monoxide and a number of carcinogenic compounds. In some places in developing countries, the pollutant exposure levels associated with indoor biomass burning is many times greater than generally accepted health standards, such as maximum particulate concentrations of 250 micrograms per cubic metre in the United States. However, in developing countries people are routinely exposed to indoor particulate concentrations many times higher. These levels rival or even exceed the pollution levels found in the most polluted industrial cities. Women and children are particularly affected, where cooking smoke is confined to indoor settings, to which they are exposed for extended hours each day. Source: WEC 57 Implications for poverty Transforming energy markets does not mean that all forms of government intervention in energy should be disowned or dismantled. That would be irresponsible and premature. Most developing countries in the region are far from achieving universal access to energy, with poor consumers particularly vulnerable to the \u201cliberation\u201d of end-user prices that have been regulated and subsidised by governments for decades under the public utility model. Any liberalisation of energy markets must, as a matter of human development priority, protect the interests of these consumers. A balanced approach to energy market transformation could simultaneously pursue market penetration and market creation, the latter directed at ensuring those enabling conditions that make it easier for the poor to make the energy transition within a predictable time frame. This would involve safeguards like subsidies and lifeline tariffs to cushion the price shocks of market liberalisation, as well as compatible measures to raise the poor\u2019s incomes so that safeguards do not become permanent aberrations of the need to reflect the scarcity value of energy in prices. The preceding assessments indicate some long-term gains to the poor in the form of higher energy consumption and access. However, the near- term losses to them in income, employment and price increases could outweigh the gains. Some would argue that this is a worthwhile trade- off, but the question is: for whom? The poor lack the most basic level of economic security in the form of assets and income. Asking them to endure higher energy prices and loss of livelihood for an uncertain number of years is not justifiable on human development grounds. The removal of pricing subsidies for energy post-liberalisation could prolong poverty, not resolve it. Misdirected subsidies clearly have a corrosive influence on efficiency as they obscure the true value of scarce energy resources. But so long as poverty remains a problem, the response to the abuse of subsidies cannot be to abolish them altogether. This is a 58 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All reality acknowledged by the World Energy Council which, while supportive of the abolition of subsidies in general, states that: \u201cGovernment or regulatory intervention in energy pricing mechanisms may be justified to address certain externalities or to achieve certain social or long-term goals. Energy subsidies, which may be necessary, must benefit those who really need them and should enhance the accessibility, availability and acceptability of energy services. Such subsidies should be visible in terms of their size, transparent in terms of their sources and beneficiaries, and subject to review within a prescribed time period.\u201d The other side of the coin is the poor\u2019s lack of income, which inhibits them from participating in the market. Rational pricing policies need to be matched by rational income policies. While energy can play a role in increasing the incomes of the poor, it does so effectively only when combined with other development inputs, implying that energy market liberalisation cannot be considered in isolation of policies in other development sectors. The overall conclusion is that market liberalisation", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ded66a4a-ca68-41da-9134-1f2e02f5ff72": {"__data__": {"id_": "ded66a4a-ca68-41da-9134-1f2e02f5ff72", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "acb22054f72961dcb9f6bcac20d230251156d0fe7505b29ebf220d65cb8d3d7b"}, "3": {"node_id": "78e3539f-3d05-4f44-b17f-bea55aa722cc", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a3ec76625cbac206fd334e383fc64b53080fe294c635f1eb4fa4c17ee515acf8"}}, "hash": "f0e2e715fb57209182ebe19cf9a4e91012d16fb4a9306b6398caa3f92ca174d8", "text": "in energy is desirable, but it needs to protect the poor\u2019s interests. While there are a number of powerful economic reasons why liberalisation should be sought, there are equally compelling reasons why governments should draw the boundaries of liberalisation to limit its adverse consequences for the poor. Creating energy markets for growth and access In the face of surging competition for international energy resources and unrelenting volatility in global energy prices, the transition to modern fuels and electricity in Asian developing countries can be accelerated only by diversifying their energy resource base, achieving higher levels of efficiency in energy production and consumption, and introducing greater competition in domestic energy markets that have historically functioned in a government-controlled monopolistic environment. Recent years have witnessed a growing sense of discontent with the concept of energy as a \u201cnatural monopoly,\u201d controlled largely by state- 59 owned energy utilities operating in highly regulated markets. The inability of this model to reach large numbers of people in spite of persistent supply expansion over the years and the limits to governmental investment capacity has prompted calls for policies to enable private investment and initiatives. Pressures to liberalise trade in energy services are an extension of these calls. This implies liberalisation of investment and trade through bound commitments in a sector traditionally viewed as strategic and central to national sovereignty. Box 10: War, Oil and Prices Dramatic losses of Middle East oil supplies did not materialise either during or after the Iraq war in 2003. OPEC members, especially Saudi Arabia and Kuwait, had committed to using their spare production capacity. The war\u2019s impact on oil infrastructures were largely confined to Iraq, but this did not eclipse the fact that sizable energy import dependence from a single region or oligopolistic supplier always remains a supply security risk. Oil prices breached projected levels in 2004 and peaked to US$70 per barrel in August 2005, and this trend is predicted to continue. High oil prices on international markets affect domestic energy prices and macroeconomic fundamentals. Costlier fuels raise input costs, damping exports from Asia, a region that accounts for 30 percent of the world economy. Growth rates are being revised downward because of higher oil prices \u2013 the forecast for Asia without Japan has reduced from 6.7 percent to at least 6.3 percent, but could fall another 0.6 percent. Partly because of rising energy costs, OECD too has forecast its growth rate at 2.6 percent compared to 2.9 percent in 2004. Issues of energy access and affordability are at the nexus between energy and poverty, and while many studies call for reform if not gradual elimination of price subsidies in petroleum products over the long term, there appears to be a dearth of literature on the short- to medium-term impact of recent oil price increases on poor people\u2019s livelihoods. Source: World Energy Assessment (2004); IHT Online, accessed 21 July 2005; UNDP Regional Energy Programme 2005 60 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All There are, however, differences between allowing the entry of domestic private providers and opening the doors to foreign investors who may have little interest in rural energy markets because of low projected returns. Trade liberalisation may facilitate the expansion of supply channels in energy, but it might do little to overcome the problem of developing countries in ensuring universal access. Governments are therefore cautious about ceding control over all elements of these channels (for example, oil pipelines or power transmission grids) to private players as they strive to strike a balance between growth and equity objectives. The uneven distribution of energy resources and disparities in the economic development status of countries offer opportunities as well as risks for developing countries. For instance, Bangladesh has no significant reserves of oil, but it has natural gas, which requires an urgent inflow of external technology and knowledge for exploitation. Nepal has abundant hydropower potential,28 but it is prohibitively expensive to extend the grid across rugged mountains to its rural majorities; trans- border sales to neighbouring India are one means of generating revenue to pursue decentralised off-grid solutions domestically. 28 It has economically feasible hydropower potential of some 42,000 MW, of which only about 600 MW has been developed so far.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "78e3539f-3d05-4f44-b17f-bea55aa722cc": {"__data__": {"id_": "78e3539f-3d05-4f44-b17f-bea55aa722cc", "embedding": null, "metadata": {