 "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "50deaabf7ef9b89982bbb75f27f0a0429e401df432ae533c96fbe771b5c7d96c"}, "3": {"node_id": "f9177895-12b6-406b-b12e-9df049334389", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "651db27b1ced8965c9cf0d9d22b184a5dc4a94fef0ee30f07d9c1c835aaebeca"}}, "hash": "a74bf8c21d414c743e29005d5453770e46658f08ce3a9e3f4daddf42d3f27565", "text": "81.20 -128.80 -26.90 21.61 199.47 - TPES (Mtoe) 1,163.37 501.89 112.73 49.47 42.42 2,285.99 10,109.59 TPES per capita (toe) 0.90 0.49 1.77 2.13 0.56 1.51 1.68 Electricity consumption per capita (kWh) 992.88 382.99 1,595.66 2,736.27 515.28 764.94 2,343.00 HDI index 0.701 0.545 0.715 0.768 0.740 Life expectancy index 0.75 0.63 0.74 0.78 0.72 Education index 0.78 0.47 0.73 0.79 0.90 Population below US$ 1/day income (%) 29.40 52.50 - 5.60 27.50 Data Sources: UNDP (1999); IEA (2002) On the other hand, the rural majorities, particularly the poor among them, in energy-exporting countries might derive no direct benefits from the added revenue flows into their government coffers so long as prevailing regimes of income and wealth distribution remain distorted. The image of a country like Nepal \u2013 with more than a third its population below the poverty line and with nearly 85 percent of the population without electricity \u2013 becoming the largest exporter of hydropower to India is a study in contrast. In fact, the poor in energy exporting countries could well shoulder a greater economic, social and environmental burden than those in the importing countries as new export-oriented production facilities (hydroelectric and oil-/gas-fired plants) add to local disruptions to livelihood and pollution. At a broader level, increased trans-border trade in energy might do little to redress prevailing rural-urban poverty gaps in both exporting and importing countries. To the contrary, it may exacerbate them given that 62 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All the primary beneficiaries on either side of the bargain will be governments, industries and urban consumers. Protecting the poor against these risks implies a careful consideration of the benefits and costs of energy trade to the poor. It may require continued regulation to shield the poor from price shocks and other potential pitfalls like physical dislocation, loss of livelihood and adverse health impacts. Trade negotiations taking place largely in relation to government-industry perceptions of priorities should enlarge the scope of their participation to include consultations with the poor, who are rarely consulted on the agreements that countries enter into on their behalf. Moving forward In the dual economies of developing countries, where a socially and economically backward rural majority coexists with a modern urban minority, the benefits of economic growth tend to coalesce among the latter. There is a risk of trade liberalisation in energy services following a similar path. However, countries in which the dual economy phenomenon is less pronounced, or those that have mitigated them to a significant extent, can experience faster growth through market-opening measures. Where such growth is accompanied by prudent social policies to safeguard the interests of the marginalised population, progress in human development is conceivable. The challenge, therefore, is to strike the right balance between growth and equity and to sequence trade liberalisation in graduated steps commensurate with levels of a country\u2019s socioeconomic resilience to market transformation. The proposals at the WTO for trade liberalisation in energy services seek broad access to markets in developing countries at a crucial juncture, when many are implementing domestic reforms with varying degrees of progress. Available evidence on the outcomes of these reforms is partial and inconclusive. However, there are signs of economic benefits occurring by way of greater efficiency in exploration, development and production activities along different branches of the energy chain (coal, oil, gas and electricity), and early competition that could potentially 63 provide improved service to consumers. There is also evidence of adverse impact, importantly, through higher consumer prices and unemployment without offsetting re-employment. In this state of flux, developing countries lack a firm basis to negotiate trade in energy services either within the WTO, or bilateral and regional trade agreements outside of it. These negotiating proposals have come at a time when developing countries need to access advanced technologies, knowledge and much-needed capital. Given that energy technology innovation remains concentrated in industrialised countries, there are opportunities in the proposals worth serious consideration. The prudent course of action is to examine them carefully with in-depth analytical inputs, identify priorities and options specific to the situations and needs of each country, and negotiate a human development-friendly quid pro quo.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f9177895-12b6-406b-b12e-9df049334389": {"__data__": {"id_": "f9177895-12b6-406b-b12e-9df049334389", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "50deaabf7ef9b89982bbb75f27f0a0429e401df432ae533c96fbe771b5c7d96c"}, "2": {"node_id": "3201b0f4-99c4-4fe5-82ab-c1cbdea940c0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a74bf8c21d414c743e29005d5453770e46658f08ce3a9e3f4daddf42d3f27565"}}, "hash": "651db27b1ced8965c9cf0d9d22b184a5dc4a94fef0ee30f07d9c1c835aaebeca", "text": "Under GATS, developing countries are under no obligation to make commitments against any of the proposals on the table. They have the right to make selective commitments that need not be even across all modes of supply, that is, cross-border supply (Mode 1), commercial presence (Mode 3) and movement of natural persons (Mode 4). Even where commitments are made, countries may schedule qualifications, reflecting their regulations and making access conditional on", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c6df1e9a-35da-483c-bae9-bd6c3e51b78b": {"__data__": {"id_": "c6df1e9a-35da-483c-bae9-bd6c3e51b78b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "65c50d2e2d2cf60307d936a00523d2f66b1dceb987e35be9756ef0edcf7a8ee5"}, "3": {"node_id": "1a96dd09-8231-4be1-9c01-2255adcb66e8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-environmental-and-energy-services-and-human-development", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "32c67bdefb48e59b792a0d91104046824af993852a88e7c339df20307928dbfd"}}, "hash": "d9650692b8cf109d33f277d03ec34e2cbc7978807bd0a402c725af44451bea69", "text": "technology transfer and other human development-oriented obligations. Countries could continue to have monopoly energy supply providers so long as they have an accompanying regulatory body whose functions are open and transparent. They may or may not commit to providing third-party access to transportation and transmission facilities. They can, if they wish to, restrict market access to foreign firms and give preference to local firms if they feel it is in their national interest. Even if they make commitments to allow market access and national treatment, they can specify exceptions that allow them the flexibility to limit that access. They may provide subsidies only to local firms, if these are indicated in the national treatment column of their schedules. Finally, they can 64 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All impose public service obligations on foreign firms as a condition for access. The lack of policy options is not the constraining factor in GATS negotiations, but rather it is insufficient policy enlightenment on the role of energy in human development. Any commitment to liberalise access to energy markets would be made as a part of an overall Single Undertaking. WTO negotiations are based on reciprocity and commitments by Asia- Pacific countries that would provide huge economic advantages to firms from developed countries. They should be contemplated only if developed countries benefiting from such access make commitments and concessions in other goods and service sectors of export interest to Asia-Pacific countries. However, priority should be given to obtaining human development- compatible commitments from developed countries in the energy sector itself. Without this basic strategic understanding, developing countries run the risk of entering negotiations with scanty information, inadequate understanding of relative policy priorities, and the possibility of making hasty commitments that may come back to haunt them. The strategy for developing countries in the region thus could involve four core components: First, market access may be limited to those parts of the energy sector that are considered most beneficial and, reciprocally, access may be sought in developed-country markets in areas where a developing country has a competitive advantage. Asian countries with skilled human resources could trade energy market access commitments for a more secure movement of their professionals to jobs abroad. Others could seek concessions in agriculture or specific labour-intensive manufactures. Second, the energy needs of certain segments of the population cannot be expected to be served by the market, and therefore, those segments should continue to enjoy price and/or capital cost subsidies, special incentives for rural distribution cooperatives, and continued monopolies in electricity transmission networks. 65 Third, many countries in Asia-Pacific are actual or potential exporters of energy with distinct needs. They should, in particular, avoid obligations that would restrict their ability to maintain dual pricing regimes, i.e., they should be able to provide energy to domestic consumers at prices below those at which they export (world prices). Fourth, given the stark facts of energy deprivation in Asian developing countries, the MDGs and the implicit priority they assign to rural energy are of overarching concern. However, this should not confine energy policies to a \u201csmall is beautiful\u201d paradigm. Small-scale energy technologies have made a negligible contribution so far to reducing income poverty. Evidence suggests that income gains are more likely to accrue to rural populations that have access to electricity and modern fuels from centralised energy systems. Attention to trade questions must therefore balance issues surrounding both centralised and decentralised energy, with a long- term focus on ensuring convergent paths between the two. 66 | Trade in Environmental and Energy Services and Human Development: Contributing to Well-Being, Growth and Access for All REFERENCES 1. Adhikari, Ratnakar. 2005. Vulnerability, Trade Integration and Human Development. Draft. UNDP Regional Centre, Colombo. 2. Asian Development Bank. 2000. Asian Environmental Outlook 2001. Discussion Draft. 3. Becker, Jasper. 