_type__": "1"}, "18bec487-cc49-493d-b830-0c74aadf6d4c": {"__data__": {"id_": "18bec487-cc49-493d-b830-0c74aadf6d4c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7cefee82b6dca68c433ae9736839598ede3408dc181b6f88de31755b24e3ea4b"}, "3": {"node_id": "bd721ed1-076d-48c6-8080-5067276d60bd", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7e515d568091b7dfccbd96adf58d5a73ea65faa81126bab262afaa3a99d3e6d6"}}, "hash": "7340b26d316e50ce400b9e484be6190a314162941e25f3d6c8d5d17705a622e8", "text": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LOCs: Experiences from Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR, and Nepali Joint Policy Brief Issue 3 - August 2008 Economic Institute of Cambodia and UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo [Asia-Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative] Least Developed Countries (LDCs) in general face numerous challenges in their attempts to diversify their exports and integrate into the global economy. One common challenge is to devise negotiating positions which help maximize gains from the various trade arrangements. Recent country-level studies commissioned by the UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo in four Asian LDCs, namely Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR and Nepal explored the potential implications of World Trade Organization (WTO) agreements, Regional Trade Agreements (RTAs), and Bilateral Trade Agreements (BTAs) for these countries. Out of these studies, a number of common challenges have emerged in relation to trade negotiations ranging from market access to Aid ForTrade (AFT). Based on the findings, this policy brief highlights a number of key negotiation issues and strategies that these LDCs can adopt to address their trade and developmental concerns. As the trade negotiation landscape is rapidly changing and significant changes have occurred in the past few months, this brief also tries to incorporate the recent developments, where applicable. WTO negotiations The Doha Ministerial Declarations, known as the Doha Development Agenda (DDA), were intended to address several trade-related development concerns of developing countries. The 2004 July Framework and the 2005 Hong Kong Ministerial Conference reaffirmed the Declarations adopted in Doha. However, the Doha Round of trade negotiations has gone through turbulent phases since it was launched in 2001. The recent failure of the mini-Ministerial Conference held in Geneva in July 2008 is testimony to difficulties in the negotiations. Although the future of trade negotiations depends on political dynamics resulting from impending elections in the major WTO Members, this brief takes the final offers that were tabled during the mini-Ministerial Conference as the basis to analyze issues of interest to the four Asian LDCs. Agriculture Agriculture has been the most contentious issue in multilateral trade negotiations. Since the agricultural sector has come under spotlight in the global political landscape due to recent increase in agricultural commodity prices, concerns over the impact of liberalization have assumed even greater salience. This sector makes a significant contribution to the Gross Domestic Product (GOP), livelihood and private consumption expenditure of the four Asian LDCs studied. Among them, however, Lao PDR, which is in the process of WTO accession, is the only net exporter of agricultural produce; the other three, which are WTO Members, are net importers. Therefore, welfare implications from the liberalization of agriculture are likely to vary depending on the relative strength of the sector including the level of import dependence of these countries. Under the WTO's Agreement on Agriculture, Members have been negotiating for agricultural trade reforms; e.g. removal of agricultural trade barriers and subsidies. While little progress has been made in further liberalizing agricultural markets, trade reforms are expected to impact negatively on net importers of agricultural commodities. For example, according to a quantitative simulation by Raihan (2007), elimination of export subsidies as agreed in the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference could result in welfare losses of USS 12 million to Bangladesh and USS6.4 million to www.undprcc.lk 1 Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies to Cambodia. As per the Revised Draft Modalities on Agriculture produced by the Chair of the agriculture negotiations on 10 July 2008, which formed the basis for the text prepared by the WTO Director General, the major subsidizers of agricultural products have been urged to reduce their domestic support by 70 to 80 percent (WTO 2008a). If and when this proposal is implemented, there could be a further increase in the import bill for net food importers, even though subsidy is not the only determinant of international price changes. Since end of subsidies is likely to increase world commodity prices, some argue that LDCs welfare losses from liberalization can be substantially mitigated by increased value of their agricultural exports. However, it should be noted that an increase in commodity prices might result in higher food import bills for countries that continue to rely predominantly on imports. The studies of four LDCs summarized in Raihan et al. (2007) found a number of agricultural commodities with significant export potential, including processed fruits and vegetables, tea, coffee, herbs and medicinal plants, organic rice, and cashew nuts.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bd721ed1-076d-48c6-8080-5067276d60bd": {"__data__": {"id_": "bd721ed1-076d-48c6-8080-5067276d60bd", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7cefee82b6dca68c433ae9736839598ede3408dc181b6f88de31755b24e3ea4b"}, "2": {"node_id": "18bec487-cc49-493d-b830-0c74aadf6d4c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7340b26d316e50ce400b9e484be6190a314162941e25f3d6c8d5d17705a622e8"}}, "hash": "7e515d568091b7dfccbd96adf58d5a73ea65faa81126bab262afaa3a99d3e6d6", "text": "High tariffs in major export markets act as inhibiting factors against export expansion of these commodities. Finally, protecting the livelihood security of farmers and largely agrarian rural communities, which are vulnerable to import surge, is another important issue for these LDCs.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dff4e372-a2aa-409a-a76c-f7a0632eebd1": {"__data__": {"id_": "dff4e372-a2aa-409a-a76c-f7a0632eebd1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a8deab1fffc0269a58f02bb7cd536240100d2da767e8af405dfae90ea4c37c7b"}, "3": {"node_id": "8a1cc2a3-9d5d-4af2-8f6e-4e368693f31b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "41965f0c52105ac753a8230dcd257e1e51adb9160535e96972c96764a0ba9889"}}, "hash": "f752cd10351379f710a82e59ee300ccfcedd6f2a4bba038330dcf330f872a2de", "text": "Therefore, the proposals of Group of 33 (G-33) developing countries, with major interests in agricultural negotiations, on Special Safeguards Measures (SSM)II and Special Products (SP) hold significance for them. Non-agricultural market access Non-Agricultural Market Access (NAMA) negotiations are proceeding towards the reduction of bound tariff rates, bringing unbound tariff rates under binding commitments, which will be subject to formula cuts, and identifying and removing Non-Tariff Barriers (NTBs). A consensus was reached at the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference on NAMA modalities to use a 'Swiss formula\" for the reduction of bound tariff rates. The recent Draft Modalities produced by the Chair of the NAMA negotiations, which formed the basis for the text proposed by the WTO Director General, recommends the coefficients of 7 to 9 for developed countries and three categories of coefficients for developing countries in the range of 20 to 25 (WTO 2008b). lf and when NAMA tariffs are reduced, they will provide additional market access opportunities for the LDCs. Although LDCs are exempted from such reduction commitments, they are expected to substantially increase their binding coverage (WTO 2005). Issue 3 August 2008 If these NAMA-related measures are implemented, they are likely to have both positive and negative impacts on the four lDCs under consideration. On the positive side, the LDCs' market access to many of the developed and developing countries will increase in selected sectors due to tariff reduction. On the negative side, they may suffer from possible preference erosion in countries such as Canada and the EU, where they currently enjoy Duty-Free and Quota-Free (DFQF) market access. Services trade liberalization Liberalization of services trade under the General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS) has important implications for all the four LDCs as services account for a significant share of their GDP. One of the major constituents of services trade-remittances-are important for these LDCs, particularly for Bangladesh where they contribute to 7.1 percent of GDP and for Nepal where the corresponding figure is 15.2 percent. However, services trade liberalization under the Mode 4 (Movement of Natural Persons) of GATS is largely being restricted by immigration regulations and barriers related to visa and work permit. In most cases, no distinction is made between temporary and permanent movement of workers, and the process involves complicated, non-transparent and costly steps to conform to labour market regulation. Furthermore, in terms of migration regulations, developed countries seem biased towards high-skilled workers. In general, the movement of low-skilled workers, which most LDCs can competitively supply, is the most restrictive. Cross-cutting issues This section deals with four distinct but inter-related issues of interest to LDCs, as they cut across most market access agenda under the WTO. Duty-free quota-free market access The 2005 Hong Kong Ministerial Declaration allows 'members facing difficulties' to reduce LDC product coverage for duty-free treatment to 97 percent of tariff lines (see WTO 2005). However, as the LDCs' exports to developed countries are concentrated on a few categories such as Ready-Made Garments (RMGs), most of their export items could be potentially excluded from such treatment under this scenario. Moreover, Asian LDCs are not granted preferential market access in the United States and thus face high tariff rates on most of their RMG exports. As per simulation results in Raihan (2007), gains from full DFQF access in the US market alone are around USS500 million for Bangladesh and USS 154 million for Cambodia. Gains for Nepal and Lao PDR would be much -------~ www.undprcc.lk 2 Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies smaller-about USS 14 million and USS6 million respectively-but still significant in terms of percentage share of RMG export revenue from the US market. In addition, the potential products identified for export diversification such as Bangladeshi generic parts/light engineering and Nepalese leather also face high tariff barriers on their export markets. likewise, Cambodia faces high tariffs on the export of cashew nuts and natural rubber to developing countries such as China and India. Since advanced developing countries are also emerging as major markets for LDCs and they are likely to maintain high tariffs even after the completion of NAMA negotiations, achieving DFQF access in such markets could be immensely beneficial to LDCs.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8a1cc2a3-9d5d-4af2-8f6e-4e368693f31b": {"__data__": {"id_": "8a1cc2a3-9d5d-4af2-8f6e-4e368693f31b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a8deab1fffc0269a58f02bb7cd536240100d2da767e8af405dfae90ea4c37c7b"}, "2": {"node_id": "dff4e372-a2aa-409a-a76c-f7a0632eebd1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f752cd10351379f710a82e59ee300ccfcedd6f2a4bba038330dcf330f872a2de"}}, "hash": "41965f0c52105ac753a8230dcd257e1e51adb9160535e96972c96764a0ba9889", "text": "For example, a recent study by Laborde (2008) estimates that full DFQF market access in five large developing countries (Brazil, China, Indialv, Mexico and South Korea) would lead to annual export gains as high as USSs.6 billion for all the LDCs. Non-tariff Barriers The NTBs, particularly in the form of regulatory requirements, quota restrictions, administrative procedures and Rules of Origin (ROO), are the major concerns for the LDCs. Due to their technical complexity and non-transparent nature, they are the most", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "38f6e20e-9c88-4a3d-9817-3a5b712c091d": {"__data__": {"id_": "38f6e20e-9c88-4a3d-9817-3a5b712c091d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "83acf80b62bf194ea2a7fc5ab5fc93121cecb6ccc92d7c4a88b67eb7f14f11ac"}, "3": {"node_id": "e2ac6ed1-90d1-4a61-a7b5-68c65d6e3b76", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9f1d62749ad3f5ba35a68d73e5b9434ce83efa6685b05c076627b2c92457fec7"}}, "hash": "b522cd2f12219c3e56202af88336f82e4c913ca44ca276c1d46573ff34ff4447", "text": "difficult barriers to challenge. Standards related NTBs such as Sanitary and Phytosanitary (SPS) restrictions act as major impediments to LDCs' exports, particularly when they are not based on scientific evidence and/or beyond the standards set by international bodies. The studies summarized in Raihan et al. (2007) found cases that developed countries impose stringent SPS requirements and other NTBs on export products from Asian LDCs. For example, developed countries, particularly the EU, impose stringent SPS requirements on Bangladesh's export of agro-processing and herbs. Cambodian rice exporters face strict SPS requirements in most of their export markets in addition to other NTBs such as import quotas in the EU and a restrictive rice import policy in Japan. Food processors from Lao PDR face SPS measures in most of their target markets. Similarly, Nepal's exports of tea and herbs to its major markets confront 100 percent incidence of NTBs. As for non-agricultural products, Bangladesh, Cambodia and Lao PDR face standards and labeling requirements in the export of handicrafts such as silk products to developed country markets including the EU and Japan. Nepal also confronts NTBs such as customs and administrative procedures in the export of leather products to its major markets. Issue 3 August 2008 ROO is another major NTB affecting Bangladesh, Cambodia and Lao PDR, and such barrier has resulted in low utilization of preferences for these LDCs. For example, their utilization rates of Everything but Arms preference given by the EU are in the range of 60 to 70 percent (Adhikari 2008). Preference erosion Since LDCs enjoy preferential market access in many developed countries- e.g. DFQF market access in Canada and the EU-tariff reductions under agriculture and NAMA negotiations would lead to preference erosion for them. As preference erosion largely depends on the value of exports, preference margin and current rate of preference utilization, Bangladesh is expected to be a major loser in EU market. For example, based on a simulation by Raihan (2007), assuming NAMA coefficients of 10 for developed countries and 20 for developing countries, Bangladesh is expected to lose USS 196 million from preference erosion. However, this loss can be offset by additional opportunities arising from DFQF market access to the United States, Japan and other developed countries as well as new opportunities that tariff reductions in developing countries would bring about. For example, Laborde (2008) shows that full DFQF treatment provided by five advanced developing countries (Brazil, China, India, Mexico and South Korea) and five developed countries (Canada, Japan, Norway, Switzerland, and the United States) would not only reduce the losses arising from preference erosion substantially but also result in large-scale net gains for the LDCs. Aid for trade Recognition that market access alone is not sufficient to help developing countries in general and LDCs in particular to export their way out of poverty led to the incorporation of the concept of AFT in the Hong Kong Ministerial Declaration. AFT is expected to help the LDCs overcome their supply-side constraints and/or to mitigate the challenges posed by multilateral trade liberalization, such as preference erosion. After the adoption of the Task Force report constituted to provide recommendation on how the initiative Umight contribute most effectively to the development dimension of the DDA u (WTO 2005), the WTO has organized three regional reviews and one global review of the initiative. While the primary responsibility of providing AFT lies with multilateral development organizations and bilateral donors, the WTO will mainly play the monitoring and surveillance role. In addition, the WTO will also be responsible for implementing the Hong Kong mandate ----------------------- www.undprcc.lk 3 Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies on Enhanced Integrated Framework (ElF), a revamped and modified version of the six multilateral agencies\"\" collaborative efforts to provide trade~related technical assistance to LDCs initiated in 1997. Considered one of the vehicles for the delivery of AFT, ElF has attracted 22 donors with a pledge totaling US$280 million, which will be utilized for building trade ~re lated capacity of the LDe,.\" Negotiation dynamics and LDes' positions The four Asian LDCs should design their trade negotiation strategies taking into account their own ground realities as well as the positions of other LDCs.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e2ac6ed1-90d1-4a61-a7b5-68c65d6e3b76": {"__data__": {"id_": "e2ac6ed1-90d1-4a61-a7b5-68c65d6e3b76", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "83acf80b62bf194ea2a7fc5ab5fc93121cecb6ccc92d7c4a88b67eb7f14f11ac"}, "2": {"node_id": "38f6e20e-9c88-4a3d-9817-3a5b712c091d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b522cd2f12219c3e56202af88336f82e4c913ca44ca276c1d46573ff34ff4447"}}, "hash": "9f1d62749ad3f5ba35a68d73e5b9434ce83efa6685b05c076627b2c92457fec7", "text": "Since it is not possible for the three LDC Members (excluding Lao PDR) to influence WTO negotiations by themselves, they should align their positions with other LDCs. In this context, the Maseru Declaration of 29 February 2008, adopted by LDC trade ministers, not only tries to strike a balance between various positions of LDCs but also provides a basis for devising common negotiation strategies. It should however, be noted that the benefits arising from the cross~ cutting issues such", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6bf2b55e-bc7d-42e5-bc02-66d4e008afef": {"__data__": {"id_": "6bf2b55e-bc7d-42e5-bc02-66d4e008afef", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f0b6d34d8a8c32263321d348a7a2ee4a8127f5318f594eb8056f924eb5fbb496"}, "3": {"node_id": "6ded1330-ccfa-4150-bfc7-b9062318b3d0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0426e713d2396acde427ed999c6472c25a1cbab8a2d439d0a6cc32285d4a7849"}}, "hash": "03840944716275c76fda34a6b225ceb2b34a577a4e57f5e86c859c336ee301d3", "text": "as DFQF market access and agreement on preference erosion proposed at Maseru are not likely to be shared equally by all the LDCs. For example, African LDCs could suffer from preference erosion in the US market, if the LDCs' proposal of full DFQF market access is implemented. Therefore, compensatory mechanisms such as preferential access to AFT resources should be proposed to the prospective losers in order to garner a broader support for common positions. Similarly, expeditious removal of cotton subsidies, which are of great concerns to African LDCs such as Benin, Burkina Faso, Chad, and Mali, will have to be taken on board to demonstrate solidarity amongst lDCs, even though cotton issue has limited significance to Asian LDCs. Some of the LDCs' concerns relating to agriculture and NAMA are best addressed specifically through appropriately designed sectoral negotiating strategies; others can be comprehensively addressed through the cross~cutting agenda. For instance, LDCs should specifically align their positions with the proposal of G-33 on SSM and SP on agricultural negotiations. As for NAMA negotiations, LDCs had better demand for full autonomy while increasing their binding coverage. On services, a major negotiation strategy for LDCs is to call for removal of restrictions on the movement of low~ skilled and se mi ~sk illed category of workers. On cross ~ cutting issues, the following common positions for WTO negotiations are of critical significance: DFQF market access: Lobby to keep most of the Issue 3 August 2008 duty-paid export items off the exclusion list. One strategy is to negotiate for DFQF access to all products with relatively high tariffs (e.g. tariff rates higher than 6 percent). At the same time, it is beneficial to demand DFQF market access in advanced developing countries. Non ~ tariff barriers: Demand ROO applicable to imports from LDCs to be transparent and simple and contribute to facilitating market access, as agreed at the Hong Kong Ministerial Conference. The Canadian ROO provision can serve as a useful model for this initiative. In addition, the removal of regulatory barriers that are higher than the internationally agreed standards and/or not backed by evidence would be beneficial to LDCs. Preference erosian: Call for an agreement to provide trade solutions such as increased market access on protected sectors, and nan~trade solutions such as increased provision for AFT based on the magnitude of preference erosion. Aid far trade: Demand additional and predictable flow of AFT to help them take advantage of trading prospects with a view to better integrating their economies into the global economy. This is applicable in the context of goods as well as services trade. RTAlBTA negotiations One of the likely consequences of the failure of the mini~m inisterial conference of the WTO and ensuing hiatus in the DDA negotiations is the proliferation of RTAs and BTAs. While the interests of LDCs are best protected within the multilateral trading system, they cannot avoid negotiating RTAs and BTAs because of the way the various forms of trade agreements are currently being negotiated. Therefore, it is equally important for them to devise a well thought out strategy for the negotiations of these agreements. Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao PDR and Nepal are members of several RTAs. For example, Bangladesh and Nepal are members of the Agreement on South Asia Free Trade Area (SAFTA) and the Bay of Bengal Initiative for Multi~Sectora l Technical and Economic Cooperation Free Trade Agreement (BIMSTEC FTA). Cambodia and Lao PDR are members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and are participating in various negotiations under the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA). However, some RTAs have not yielded the expected trade expansion. SAFTA, for example, is unlikely to expand regional trade because most highly~traded items and other items with trade potential are included in the sensitive lists by most countries. In addition, prospects for trade in other products that generally face low tariffs are ------------------------- www.undprcc.lk 4 Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies by NTBs. In 2004, the share of intra-regional trade as a portion of the total trade of the South Asian countries was 4.5 percent compared to the corresponding figure of 22 percent for ASEAN members (Raihan et al. 2007). Likewise, in the case of BIMSTEC FTA, there has not been much progress in terms of the implementation of commitments made.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6ded1330-ccfa-4150-bfc7-b9062318b3d0": {"__data__": {"id_": "6ded1330-ccfa-4150-bfc7-b9062318b3d0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f0b6d34d8a8c32263321d348a7a2ee4a8127f5318f594eb8056f924eb5fbb496"}, "2": {"node_id": "6bf2b55e-bc7d-42e5-bc02-66d4e008afef", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "03840944716275c76fda34a6b225ceb2b34a577a4e57f5e86c859c336ee301d3"}}, "hash": "0426e713d2396acde427ed999c6472c25a1cbab8a2d439d0a6cc32285d4a7849", "text": "Since trade in goods alone is not likely to provide benefits to the LDCs, SAFTA is embarking on the path of negotiating services agreements as well as signing an investment protection agreement, following ASEAN models. However, there is a growing realization that it is equally important for SAFTA to focus on broader areas of economic cooperation including energy,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dc367bf1-7e50-4485-b31b-2553db00c438": {"__data__": {"id_": "dc367bf1-7e50-4485-b31b-2553db00c438", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies for Asian LDCs - Joint Policy Brief Issue 3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fd490ffe3cc1ba2c609e8fced26cca224a0bb8fe985d57c512c41305b0baee8c"}, "3": {"node_id": "caf52fb3-19a8-4129-ba6d-5f0e886751a4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/trade-negotiation-issues-and-strategies-asian-ldcs-joint-policy-brief-issue-3", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "98e21afffe5d53189211cca72dbb74215014990d6885b34cd62fd2d673bdd1b9"}}, "hash": "8f80258ef98dcd3971372cad741c09e28e5e83add09434027976d45b145ad2ad", "text": "infrastructure, standard setting and trade facilitation measures to reduce the cost of doing business. One of the services sectors, tourism, is of immense significance to all the three LOCs except Bangladesh. RTAs may prove mutually beneficial when the regions such as ASEAN and South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) are developed as common destination for tourists. While ASEAN tourism cooperation has been in operation since 1976, SAARC has been slow in this respectvii Accordingly, ASEAN LOCs are far ahead in terms of realizing this objective. For example, Cambodia recently signed a bilateral Single Visa agreement with Thailand with a view to increasing tourist flow. Besides, regional cooperation to enhance supply capacity in LDC member countries in the areas of infrastructure, transportation and vocational training is also crucial. These LDCs have also been engaged in several BTA negotiations with neighbouring countries and/or countries in the North. As for BTA negotiations, South-South BTAs can bring benefits to the LDCs. For example, the trade treaty between India and Nepal provides preferential market access for products manufactured in Nepal through the elimination of basic customs duties and quantitative restrictions on the basis of non-reciprocity (except for items on the negative list). As a result, trade between two countries has increased, albeit at the cost of growing trade deficit with the balance tilting in favour of India. In order to address this problem, both the countries are now contemplating to enter into a Comprehensive Economic Partnership Agreement. There are, however, concerns whether North-South BTAs will be beneficial for the LOCs. Some studies have indicated that BTAs between developed and developing countries can result in trade diversion for the weaker partners (UNESCAP 2007). Likewise, others have argued that due to inherently asymmetric negotiating prowess, Issue 3 August 2008 stronger partners can impose their will, including several WTO-plus conditions on services liberalization, competition and investment policies, environment and labour standards and intellectual property rights, which are detrimental to the interests of the weaker partners (Gibbs and Wagle 2006). Based on the analysis presented above, the negotiating position for South Asian LOCs within the regional trading arrangements should focus on deepening and broadening the areas of cooperation on other economic issues, besides pushing for the reduction of sensitive lists as well as removal of NTBs. ASEAN LOCs, which encounter limited market access restrictions within the Region, should focus on improving their supply capacity. As far as South-South BTAs are concerned, the LOCs should not only press for non-reciprocal preferential market access to the developing partner country, but also engage in more comprehensive economic cooperation. However, the LOCs need to conduct a development impact assessment as well as prepare a well informed negotiation position based on multi-stakeholder consultations before entering into a BTA with a developed country partner. The way forward The negotiation issues of Bangladesh, Cambodia, Lao POR, and Nepal, are generally in sync with the positions of other LDCs at the multilateral level. Even where differences exist, they are not of the magnitude that cannot be reconciled. Since DFQF market access is the single major agenda for the Asian LDCs, they should be prepared to address the concerns of African LDCs on the removal of cotton subsidies and preference erosion in order to maintain cohesiveness among LOCs. Similarly, developing a common position on other issues relating to agriculture, NAMA, services negotiations, ROO and NTBs, in which all the LOCs have the same position, is not likely to prove difficult. While South-South RTAs and BTAs are likely to produce benefits to the LDCs, deepening and broadening of the areas of economic cooperation are necessary to realize the true potential of these arrangements. However, due to trade diverting nature and negotiation dynamics that are tilted in favour of stronger players, the LOCs need to be extremely cautious while signing North-South BTAs. Finally, it is necessary to sound a note of caution. Given the fact that these LOCs have limited institutional capacity and negotiating capital, it is necessary for them to prioritize the negotiating fora as a part of an overall negotiation strategy in order to obtain maximum advantage from trade negotiations. ----------------------- www.undprcc.lk 5 Trade Negotiation Issues and Strategies References Adhikari, Ratnakar. 2008. uThe Local Content Paradox at the WTO: A Minor Lapse or Organised Hypocrisy?,\" BRIDGE Monthly Review. Vol. 12.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "caf52fb3-19a8-4129-ba6d-5f0e886751a4": {"__data__": {"id_": "caf52fb3-19a8-4129-ba6d-5f0e886751a4", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asi